\begin_layout Standard
Since the title of this book is 'Soft Materials', it makes sense to define
 what we really mean by 'soft'.
 Here are two ways to think about it:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Soft materials have low elastic moduli.

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
By 'low' we mean significantly lower than the moduli of crystalline metals
 and ceramics.

\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hyperlink{Youngs_modulus}{Young's modulus}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for crystalline ceramic or metallic materials.
 The jellyfish shown in Fig.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:jellyfish"

\end_inset

 is obvioulsy 'soft' in this sense.
 Metals and ceramics typically have moduli in the range of 100 MPa (see
 Fig.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:range of moduli"

\end_inset

).
 While the strength of metals can be adjusted by a variety of mechanisms
 that affect the nature of dislocation motion in these systems, the the
 modulus is set by the nature of the interatomic potentials and there nothing
 that can really be done to significantly affect the modulus of a given
 material.
 Polymers are different, however, and have a much broader range of elastic
 moduli.
 The stiffest of these (Kevlarâ„¢for example) have elastic moduli in at least
 one direction that are comparable to the modulus of steel.

\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate-Resume

\series bold
Thermal fluctuations matter in soft materials.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
At a molecular level, the relevant energy scale that determines a variety
 of important properties is the thermal energy,
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Boltmann's Constant
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$k_{B}$"
description "Boltzmann's constant"

\end_inset

 Boltzmann's constant and
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "T"
description "Absolute temperature"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the absolute temperature.
 If different molecular arrangements within a material differ in energy
 by an amount that of the order of
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

 or less, than these different arrangements will all be experienced by the
 material.
 When the free energy of a material is dominated by the entropy associated
 with the accessibility of these different arrangements, it is possible
 to calculate the elastic properties of the material from the molecular
 structure with considerable accuracy.
 The best example of this is our discussion of
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sub:rubber elasticity"

\end_inset

.

\end_layout

\end_deeper
