\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Exercise:
\series default
How high above the earths surface must a single oxygen molecule be lifted
 in order for its gravitational potential energy to be increased by
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Solution:
\series default
 The gravitational potential energy is
\begin_inset Formula $mgh$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the mass of the object,
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the gravitational acceleration (9.8 m/s
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

) and
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is height.
 The mass of a single
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

 molecule is obtained by dividing the molecular weight in g/mole by Avogadro's
 number:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula
\[
m=32\left(\frac{\mathrm{g}}{\mathrm{mole}}\right)\left(\frac{\mathrm{mole}}{6.02x10^{23}}\right)=5.3x10^{-23}\,\mathrm{g}=5.3x10^{-26}\,\mathrm{kg}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The conversion to kg illustrates the first point that we want to make with
 this simple calculation:
\series bold
Don't mix units and convert everything to SI units (m-kg-s) to keep yourself
 sane and avoid unit errors.

\series default
 Boltmann's constant,
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}$
\end_inset

 needs to be in SI units as well:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula
\[
k_{B}=1.38x10^{-23}\,\mathrm{J/K}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Now we just need to equate
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

 to
\begin_inset Formula $mgh$
\end_inset

, using something reasonable for the absolute temperature,
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 I'll use
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

=300 K to get the following:
\begin_inset Formula
\[
h=\frac{k_{B}T}{mg}=\frac{\left(1.38x10^{-23}\,\textrm{J/K}\right)\left(300\,\mathrm{K}\right)}{\left(5.3x10^{-26}\,\mathrm{kg}\right)\left(9.8\mathrm{\,m/s^{2}}\right)}=8000\,\mathrm{m}=8\,\mathrm{km}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The full oxygen partial pressure is given proportional to
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(-mgh/k_{B}T)$
\end_inset

, so this value of
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the altitude where the oxygen pressure is a factor of
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 (2.7) less than the value at sea level.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Exercise:altitude effect on pressure"

\end_inset


\end_layout

