status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
M Evolution during Step Growth
\end_layout

\end_inset

Molecular Weight Evolution during Step Growth Polymerization
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Maximum--for"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}$
\end_inset

 moles of difunctional A molecules with molecuar weight
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 react with
\begin_inset Formula $n_{b}$
\end_inset

 difunctional B molecules with molecular weight
\begin_inset Formula $M_{b}$
\end_inset

 in a step growth polymerization.
 If
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}$
\end_inset

 >
\begin_inset Formula $n_{b}$
\end_inset

, then all of the B molecules can react, and
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}-n_{b}$
\end_inset

 molecules will remain at the end of the polymerization:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\[
n^{min}=n_{a}-n_{b}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For condensation reactions, a mole of condensation product with molecular
 weight
\begin_inset Formula $M_{c}$
\end_inset

 material as a wholeecule of B that reacts.
 The total weight,
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, of polymer produced is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
w=n_{a}M_{a}+n_{b}M_{b}-2n_{b}M_{c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximum number average molecular weight,
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}^{max}$
\end_inset

, is obtained by using this value for
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, an setting
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 equal to
\begin_inset Formula $n_{min}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
M_{n}^{max}=\frac{w}{n^{min}}=\frac{n_{a}M_{a}+n_{b}M_{b}-2n_{b}M_{c}}{n_{a}-n_{b}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For high molecular weight polymers, we can make some additional approximations,
 since know that
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}-n_{b}$
\end_inset

 <<
\begin_inset Formula $n_{b}$
\end_inset

 in this case.
 We can therefore simplify
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}$
\end_inset

 to the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
M_{n}^{max}\approx\frac{n_{b}\left(M_{a}+M_{b}-2M_{c}\right)}{n_{a}-n_{b}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The repeat unit molecular weight,
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}$
\end_inset

 is obtained by adding the molecular weights for the A and B monomers, and
 subtracting out the molecular weight of the 2 condensation products that
 are formed (since a repeat unit contains 2 A-B linkages, and therefore
 involves 2 condensation reactions):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
M_{0}=M_{a}+M_{b}-2M_{c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this we obtain the following expression for
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}^{max}$
\end_inset

 :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
M_{n}^{max}\approx\frac{n_{a}M_{0}}{n_{a}-n_{b}}\label{eq:Mn max for step growth}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next thing we would like to sort out is how
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the total number of molecules, varies with the extent of reaction,
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The trick is to realize that every time a reaction takes place, the number
 of molecules in the system decreases by 1.
 Each molecule has two groups (one at each end) that can react, and two
 groups take part in each reaction.
 For
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 we obtain the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
n=n_{a}+n_{b}-p\left(n_{a}+n_{b}\right)=\left(n_{a}+n_{b}\right)\left(1-p\right)\label{eq:n vs. p for step growth}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this equation
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}+n_{b}$
\end_inset

 is the initial number of molecules that we start off with (when
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

=0), and
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(n_{a}+n_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 gives the decrease in the number of molecules resulting from all of the
 reactions that have taken place for some finite value of
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The total mass of the polymer that has been produced is
\begin_inset Formula $\approx\left(n_{a}+n_{b}\right)M_{0}/2$
\end_inset

 (ignoring the fact that the ends of all the molecules some extra mass that
 may potentially leave as part of a condensation product).
 The weight average molecular weight is simply
\begin_inset Formula $w/n$
\end_inset

, from which we obtain the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
M_{n}=\frac{w}{n}=\frac{(n_{a}+n_{b})M_{0}}{2(n_{a}+n_{b})(1-p)}=\frac{M_{0}}{2(1-p)}\label{eq:Mn vs. p}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As mentioned above, the degree of polymerization that can be obtained from
 a homogeneous mixture of A and B monomers in a linear stop growth polymerizatio
n is limited by stoichiometry.
 Reaction of all A monomers requires the existence of unreacted B monomers,
 and
\emph on
vice versa
\emph default
.
 If
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}\ne n_{b}$
\end_inset

, then some of the functional groups on either the A or B monomers must
 remain unreacted, so that
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has a maximum value somewhat less than 1.
 Let's consider the case where
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}-n_{b}$
\end_inset

, in which case we know there are
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}-n_{b}$
\end_inset

molecules left when all the B groups have reacted.
 Each of these molecules has an unreacted A group at each end, so there
 are a total of
\begin_inset Formula $2\left(n_{a}-n_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 unreacted groups at the end of the reaction.
 At the beginning of the reaction (when
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

=0) we had
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}+n_{b}$
\end_inset

 reactive groups, so the total number that have reacted is
\begin_inset Formula $2\left(n_{a}+n_{b}\right)-2(n_{a}-n_{b})=4n_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 This corresponds to a fraction of reacted groups which we refer to as
\begin_inset Formula $p^{max}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
p^{max}=\frac{4n_{b}}{2\left(n_{a}+n_{b}\right)}=\frac{2n_{b}}{n_{a}+n_{b}}\label{eq:pmax}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to obtain
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}^{max}$
\end_inset

 is to use Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Mn vs. p"

\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}$
\end_inset

, with
\begin_inset Formula $p=p^{max}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
M_{n}^{max}=\frac{M_{0}}{2(1-p_{max})}=\frac{M_{0}(n_{a}+n_{b}}{2\left((n_{a}-n_{b}\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which with
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}\approx n_{b}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Mn max for step growth"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the information given so far we know how the number average degree
 of polymerization evolves with
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, but in many cases we would like to know what the full molecular weight
 distribution might look like.
 To do this we need to account for the statistics, and use the more detailed
 definitions for
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}$
\end_inset

 (Eq.
 ) and
\begin_inset Formula $M_{w}$
\end_inset

 (Eq.
 ) A molecule formed from a linear step growth polymerization that has a
 degree of polymerization of
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 was made from
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 molecules (
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of type A and
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of type B).
 Because these
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 original molecules are all bifunctional, there are a total of
\begin_inset Formula $4N$
\end_inset

 reactive groups in the monomers that reacted together to form a polymer
 of length
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Only two of these groups remain unreacted (the end groups).
 Because each reaction involves two groups, this means that
\begin_inset Formula $2N-1$
\end_inset

 reactions have taken place (
\begin_inset Formula $4N-2$
\end_inset

 groups have reacted).

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key assumption is that all groups react with equal probability.
 This probability must therefore be equal to the fraction of functional
 groups which has reacted, which has already been defined as the extent
 of reaction,
\emph on
p
\emph default
.
 The probability that any single one of these
\begin_inset Formula $2N-1$
\end_inset

 reactions has taken place is therefore equal to
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We have to multiply all of these probabilities together to get the probability
 of having a polymer with a degree of polymerization of
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, so we end up with the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
n_{N}\propto p^{2N-1}\label{eq:ideal nN  distribution for step growth}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The weight,
\begin_inset Formula $w_{N}$
\end_inset

, corresponding to each fraction is proportional to
\begin_inset Formula $n_{N}N$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
w_{N}\alpha Np^{2N-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The shapes of these distributions for
\begin_inset Formula $n_{N}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $w_{N}$
\end_inset

 are shown in the plots below, and can be replotted with different values
