\begin_layout Subsection
Corothers Theory of Gelation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Corothers-Theory-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}$
\end_inset

 molecules with a reactive functionality of
\begin_inset Formula $f_{a}$
\end_inset

 that are able to react with
\begin_inset Formula $n_{b}$
\end_inset

 molecules with a reactive functionality of
\begin_inset Formula $f_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 For illustrative purposes, consider the perfectly stoichiometric case where
 the total functionality of all the A monomers is equal to the total functionali
ty of all the B monomers:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
n_{a}f_{a}=n_{b}f_{b}\label{eq:nonlinear step growth - stoichiometric balance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define an average reactive functionality,
\begin_inset Formula $f_{av}$
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n_{a}+n_{b}\right)f_{av}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the total number of functional groups:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left(n_{a}+n_{b}\right)f_{av}=n_{a}f_{a}+n_{b}f_{b}\label{eq:nonlinear step growth average functionality}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number of initial molecules corresponding to a given number of functional
 groups is inversely proportional to
\begin_inset Formula $f_{av}$
\end_inset

.
 For large values of
\begin_inset Formula $f_{av}$
\end_inset

, p does not have to reach unity in order for the total number of molecules
 to be reduced to one.
 An expression for
\begin_inset Formula $N_{n}$
\end_inset

 can be obtained substituting p
\begin_inset Formula $f_{av}$
\end_inset

/2 for
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 , describing the evolution of
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}$
\end_inset

 with
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for linear step growth polymerization:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
N_{n}=\frac{1}{2-pf_{av}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantity
\begin_inset Formula $pf_{av}$
\end_inset

 describes the average number of times that any given molecule has reacted.
 The number average molecular weight is predicted to diverge to infinity
 when this average number of reactions per molecule is 2.
 This occurs when
\begin_inset Formula $p=p_{gel}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula $p_{gel}$
\end_inset

Standardextent of reaction at the endpoint.
 Setting
\begin_inset Formula $p_{gel}f_{av}=2$
\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
p_{gel}=\frac{2}{f_{av}}\label{eq:nonlinear step growth gel point}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This simple equation for the gel point is very useful, although it is important
 to remember that this derivation suffers from the following deficiencies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Gelation actually occurs for finite
\begin_inset Formula $N_{n}$
\end_inset

, since
\begin_inset Formula $N=\infty$
\end_inset

 only for the largest molecule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The theory neglects loop formation (reactions between two portions of the
 same molecule).
 These reactions change the shape of a given molecule, but do not decrease
 the overall number of molecules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first assumption tends to overestimate
\begin_inset Formula $p_{gel}$
\end_inset

, and the second assumption tends to underestimate
\begin_inset Formula $p_{gel}$
\end_inset

.
 A more accurate description of gelation requires a much more detailed theory
 than the one presented here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When one molecule which spans the entire sample, it can no longer flow like
 a liquid.
 One the characteristics of non-linear step growth polymerizations is that
 the viscosity (resistance to flow) of the reaction mixture increases as
 the extent of reaction increases, and eventually diverges at the gel point.
 Also, the reaction rate generally decreases as the reaction proceeds and
 the reactive molecules become larger and larger.
 These features are illustrated conceptually in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:nonlinear step-growth properties"

\end_inset

.
 Here we show schematic representations of the time-dependent extent of
 reaction, along with the time dependence of the number average degree of
 polymerization,
\begin_inset Formula $N_{n}$
\end_inset

, and of two physical properties of the material:
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Here
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the limiting viscosity measured at very low shear rates, and
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is the elastic modulus measured at very long times.
 The viscosity is a characteristic of a liquid material, and characterizes
 the material for values of the extent of reaction,
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, that are less than the extent of reaction corresponding to the gel point,

\begin_inset Formula $p_{gel}$
\end_inset

.
 For values of
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 that exceed
\begin_inset Formula $p_{gel}$
\end_inset

, the material behaves as a solid, and has a finite elastic modulus,
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 At the gel point, the viscosity diverges to infinity, since it is no longer
 possible for the material to flow.
 Instead, the material becomes an elastic solid, with a value of
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 that increases from 0 at the gel point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that that materials near the gel point are viscoelastic, and can no
 longer be described by a single value of the viscosity or modulus.
 Instead, these properties depend on the timescale of the measurement, as
 described in more detail on the section on viscoelasticity.
\end_layout

