\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 describes the linear relationship between the change in volume in the change
 in temperature:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta V}{V}=\alpha\Delta T
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the glassy phase (
\begin_inset Formula $T<T_{g}$
\end_inset

), the free volume is assumed to remain constant, so that increases in the
 volume are governed entirely by increases in the occupied volume:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta V_{occ}}{V}=\alpha\Delta T\label{eq:thermal expansion - glass}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the liquid phase (
\begin_inset Formula $T>T_{g}$
\end_inset

), the free volume and occupied volumes both increase with temperature,
 and we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta V}{V}=\frac{\Delta V_{f}}{V}+\frac{\Delta V_{occ}}{V}=\alpha_{\ell}\Delta T\label{eq:thermal expansion - liquid}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:thermal expansion - glass"

