\begin_layout Subsection
Random Walk in One Dimension
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Random Walk in One Dimension
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:One-Dimensional-Random-Walk"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can understand much of what we need to understand by considering the
 simplest case of a random walk in 1 dimension.
 In this case our 'walker' takes
\begin_inset Formula $N_{x}$
\end_inset

 steps, each of which is a randomly chosen move to either the left or right.
 At the end of these
\begin_inset Formula $N_{x}$
\end_inset

steps we write down how many steps removed from the starting point our walker
 is.
 We refer to this number as
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if the walker ends up 4 steps to the right of where he ended
 up, then
\begin_inset Formula $i=4.$
\end_inset

 Where our walker ended up after one particular trip is not very important
 though.
 We need to have him take lots of trips, and collect statistics to see where
 he ended up after taking a large number of trips.
 We'll let him take a total of
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 trips, and write down the number of times,
\begin_inset Formula $n,$
\end_inset

 that the walker has ended up
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 steps from where we started.
 If the walk is really random, then the relationship between
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 will be approximated by Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1d random walk distribution"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Random Walk Animation 2.png
	width 70text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Random walk animation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
n(i)=2M\left(\frac{1}{2\text{\pi}N_{x}}\right)^{1/2}\exp\left(\frac{-i^{2}}{2N_{x}}\right)\label{eq:1d random walk distribution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can check that the summation is appropriately normalized.
 In other words, is the following expression valid?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\underset{i}{\sum}n_{i}=M\label{eq:normlization condition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The summation here is over all possible values of
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 .
 Note that for a random walk with an even number of steps, only even values
 of
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 are possible.
 Similarly, for a walk with an odd number of steps, only odd values of
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 are possible.
 We can get the summation we want by summing over all integer values of

\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and then dividing by two:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\underset{i}{\sum}n(i)=\frac{M}{\sqrt{2\pi N_{x}}}\overset{\infty}{\underset{i=-\infty}{\sum}}\exp\left(\frac{-i^{2}}{2N_{x}}\right)\approx\frac{M}{\sqrt{2\pi N_{x}}}\overset{\infty}{\underset{-\infty}{\int}}\exp\left(\frac{-i^{2}}{2N_{x}}\right)di\label{eq:1d walk discrete gaussian sum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Functions of the form
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)\propto\exp-\left(x/A\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 (where
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a constant) are called Gaussian functions, and generally describe random
 processes.
 The following integrals of a Gaussian function will be very useful for
 us:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\overset{\infty}{\underset{-\infty}{\int}}\exp-\left(x/A\right)^{2}dx=A\sqrt{\pi}\,\,\,\mathrm{(a)}\\
\overset{\infty}{\underset{-\infty}{\int}}x\exp-\left(x/A\right)^{2}dx=0\,\,\,\mathrm{(b)}\\
\overset{\infty}{\underset{-\infty}{\int}}x^{2}\exp-\left(x/A\right)^{2}dx=A^{3}\sqrt{\pi}/2\,\,\,\mathrm{(c)}
\end{array}\label{eq:gaussian integrals}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our case,
\begin_inset Formula $A=\sqrt{2N_{x}}$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \sum_{i}n\left(i\right)=M}$
\end_inset

 and our expression for the Gaussian distribution of random walks is indeed
 normalized.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Average of a Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The entire distribution represented by the Gaussian function will be useful
 to us, but it is still useful to have some averages.
 We encountered averages already in our discussion of the number and weight
 average distribution.
 In general, if
\begin_inset Formula $Pr(x)$
\end_inset

 is the probability that a function has a value of
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, than the average value of
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (referred to as
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

) is obtained from the following expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle x\right\rangle =\underset{x}{\sum}xPr\left(x\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the sum is over all possible values of
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, the average of
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by:
