\begin_layout Subsection
Averages for Random Walks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the length of each step taken by the random walker is
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, then the distance between the beginning and the end of the walk is simply

\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 times this step length:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\[
R_{x}=ia
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can substitute
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}/a$
\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $dR_{x}/a$
\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $di$
\end_inset

 in Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1d walk discrete gaussian sum"

\end_inset

 to get an expression for the total number of walks
\begin_inset Formula $M.$
\end_inset

 We'll generalize a bit further and replace the limits of
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to limits of
\begin_inset Formula $R_{min}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $R_{max}$
\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain the following for
\begin_inset Formula $M\left(R_{min},\,R_{max}\right)$
\end_inset

, the total number of walks with values of
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}$
\end_inset

 between
\begin_inset Formula $R_{min}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $R_{max}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
M\left(R_{min},\,R_{max}\right)=M\overset{R_{max}}{\underset{R_{min}}{\int}}Pr\left(R_{x}\right)dR_{x}\label{eq:1d walk gaussian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with the probability density function,
\begin_inset Formula $Pr\left(R_{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 given as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
Pr\left(R_{x}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi N_{x}a^{2}}}\exp\left(\frac{-R_{x}^{2}}{2N_{x}a^{2}}\right)\label{eq:1d walk gaussian-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity, it is helpful to define
\begin_inset Formula $A=\sqrt{2N_{x}a^{2}}$
\end_inset

 so that we can write
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(R_{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
Pr\left(R_{x}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}A}\exp-\left(R_{x}/A\right)^{2}\label{eq:1d walk gaussian-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To calculate the average values of
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

, referred to as
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R_{x}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R_{x}^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, respectively, we use Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:average of a continuous function"

\end_inset

 to calculate the averages:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle R_{x}\right\rangle =\overset{\infty}{\underset{-\infty}{\int}}R_{x}Pr(R_{x})dR_{x}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}A}\overset{\infty}{\underset{-\infty}{\int}}R_{x}\exp-\left(R_{x}/A\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle R_{x}^{2}\right\rangle =\overset{\infty}{\underset{-\infty}{\int}}R_{x}^{2}Pr(R_{x})dR_{x}==\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}A}\overset{\infty}{\underset{-\infty}{\int}}R_{x}^{2}\exp-\left(R_{x}/A\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we use the standard integrals to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle R_{x}\right\rangle =0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle R_{x}^{2}\right\rangle =\frac{A^{2}}{2}=N_{x}a^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that the first result has to be true because the Gaussian distribution
 function is symmetric: positive and negative values of
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}$
\end_inset

 with equal magnitudes are equally likely.
 This means that any contribution to
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R_{x}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 will be exactly offset by a contribution with the opposite sign.
 For this reason, the mean-square end-to-end distance,
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R_{x}^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 , or the root mean square end-to-end distance,
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R_{x}^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 , is typically used to describe the spatial extent of a random walk.
\end_layout

