\begin_layout Standard
Much of our understanding of amorphous polymers is based on our treatment
 of individual molecules as random walks in three dimensions.
 We assume that we can treat a polymer of degree of polymerization
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 as a random walk of
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 steps, each with an effective length of
\begin_inset Formula $a,$
\end_inset

 which we refer to as the
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Statistical segment length
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Statistical segment length
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The statistical segment length does not correspond to a real polymer dimension
 that we can get directly by looking at the structure of the polymer molecule.
 We need more detailed models of chain dimensions for that.
 For now, you just need to know that it is a length that gives the right
 overall molecular size.
 To simplify our treatment and make the connection back to the statistics
 that we already developed for one-dimensional random walks, we make the
 following simplifying assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We will get the overall statistics right by assuming a simple lattice model
 (as in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2-D-Random-Walk"

\end_inset

), where the a chain is able to movie in any of the x, y or z directions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Of the
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 steps made by the chain,
\begin_inset Formula $N/3$
\end_inset

 of them move in each of the x, y and z directions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value of
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}$
\end_inset

 that we studied in the one dimensional random walk case is just the x component
 of the end-to-end vector, which also has y and z components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\vec{R}=R_{x}\hat{x}+R_{y}\hat{y}+R_{z}\hat{z}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 are unit vectors in the x, y and z directions, respectively.
 The probability that a given random walk of N steps in three dimensions
 has an end-to end vector of with x, y and z compenents of
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $R_{y}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $R_{z}$
\end_inset

 is given by multiplying the probabilities for the individual components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
Pr(R_{x},\,R_{y},\,R_{z})=Pr(R_{x})Pr(R_{y})Pr(R_{z})=(2\pi Na^{2}/3)^{-3/2}\exp\left(\frac{-3R^{2}}{2Na^{2}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where we have used the following relationships:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
R^{2}=R_{x}^{2}+R_{y}^{2}+R_{z}^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
N_{x}=N_{y}=N_{z}=N/3
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This relationship can be further simplified by recalling that
\begin_inset Formula $Pr(R_{x},R_{y},R_{z})dR_{x}dR_{y}dR_{z}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that x component of the end-to-end vector is between

\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}+dx$
\end_inset

, the y component is between
\begin_inset Formula $R_{y}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $R_{y}+dy$
\end_inset

, and the z component is between
\begin_inset Formula $R_{z}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $R_{z}+dz$
\end_inset

.
 Because the probability only depends on
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 for an isotropic system (as must be the case for a truly random walk),
 we can substitute
\begin_inset Formula $4\pi R^{2}dR$
\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $dR_{x}dR_{y}dR_{z}$
\end_inset

 to obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
Pr(R)=\frac{3(6)^{1/2}R^{2}}{\text{Ï€}^{1/2}(Na^{2})^{3/2}}\exp\left(\frac{-3R^{2}}{2Na^{2}}\right)=\frac{4.15R^{2}}{R_{0}^{3}}\exp\left(\frac{-3R^{2}}{2R_{0}^{2}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula $Pr\left(R\right)dR$
\end_inset

 is the probability that the magnitude of the end-to-end vector lies between

\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $R+dR$
\end_inset

, and we have used the following definition of
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
