\begin_layout Subsection
General Considerations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are interested in the average magnitude of the end-to-end vector.
 As discussed in the previous section, the average of
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{R}$
\end_inset

 itself is not useful, since it just averages to zero.
 We are interested in the average value of the square of the magnitude of
 the end-to end vector.
 This quantity is equal to the dot product of the end-to-end vector with
 itself:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
R^{2}=\vec{R}\cdot\vec{R}=\left(\vec{r}_{1}+\vec{r}_{2}+\vec{r}_{3}+...+\vec{r}_{N_{b}}\right)\cdot\left(\vec{r}_{1}+\vec{r}_{2}+\vec{r}_{3}+...+\vec{r}_{N_{b}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dot product has
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}^{2}$
\end_inset

 terms, which can be represented in the following matrix form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
R^{2}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ccccc}
\vec{r}_{1}\cdot\vec{r}_{1} & +\vec{r}_{1}\cdot\vec{r}_{2} & +\vec{r}_{1}\cdot\vec{r}_{3} & +... & +\vec{r}_{1}\cdot\vec{r}_{N_{b}}\\
+\vec{r}_{2}\cdot\vec{r}_{1} & +\vec{r}_{2}\cdot\vec{r}_{2} & +\vec{r}_{2}\cdot\vec{r}_{3} & +... & +\vec{r}_{2}\cdot\vec{r}_{N_{b}}\\
+\vec{r}_{3}\cdot\vec{r}_{1} & +\vec{r}_{3}\cdot\vec{r}_{2} & +\vec{r}_{3}\cdot\vec{r}_{3} & +... & +\vec{r}_{3}\cdot\vec{r}_{N_{b}}\\
+... & +... & +... & +... & +...\\
+\vec{r}_{N_{b}}\cdot\vec{r}_{1} & +\vec{r}_{N_{b}}\cdot\vec{r}_{2} & +\vec{r}_{N_{b}}\cdot\vec{r}_{3} & +... & +\vec{r}_{N_{b}}\cdot\vec{r}_{N_{b}}
\end{array}\right\}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dot product between two vectors,
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{A}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{B}$
\end_inset

 is given in general by
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\vec{A}\right|\left|\vec{B}\right|\cos\theta$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the angle between the two vectors, illustrated below in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:vector angle"

\end_inset

.
 At this point we will make our first simplifying assumption, which is that
 the lengths of all bonds along the backbone are identical.
 This assumption is certainly valid for vinyl polymers, and other polymers
 which have only C-C single bonds along the backbone.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Dot_Product.svg
	width 25text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Definition of the angle between two vectors.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:vector angle"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If this bond length is
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be represented as follows, where
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the angle between bond
\emph on
i
\emph default
 and bond
\emph on
j
\emph default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
R^{2}=\ell^{2}\left\{ \begin{array}{ccccc}
\cos\theta_{11} & +\cos\text{\theta}_{12} & +\cos\text{\theta}_{13} & +... & +\cos\text{\theta}_{1N_{b}}\\
+\cos\theta_{21} & +\cos\text{\theta}_{22} & +\cos\text{\theta}_{23} & +... & +\cos\text{\theta}_{2N_{b}}\\
+\cos\theta_{31} & +\cos\text{\theta}_{32} & +\cos\text{\theta}_{33} & +... & +\cos\text{\theta}_{3N_{b}}\\
+... & +... & +... & +... & +...\\
+\cos\theta_{N_{b}1} & +\cos\text{\theta}_{N_{b}2} & +\cos\theta_{N_{b}3} & +... & +\cos\text{\theta}_{N_{b}N_{b}}
\end{array}\right\}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The average value of R, will be determined by the average values of Î¸
\begin_inset Formula $_{ij}$
\end_inset

 In mathematical terms, we have the following expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle =\ell^{2}\left\{ \begin{array}{ccccc}
\left\langle \cos\theta_{11}\right\rangle  & +\left\langle \cos\text{\theta}_{12}\right\rangle  & +\left\langle \cos\text{\theta}_{13}\right\rangle  & +... & +\left\langle \cos\text{\theta}_{1N_{b}}\right\rangle \\
+\left\langle \cos\theta_{21}\right\rangle  & +\left\langle \cos\text{\theta}_{22}\right\rangle  & +\left\langle \cos\text{\theta}_{23}\right\rangle  & +... & +\left\langle \cos\text{\theta}_{2N_{b}}\right\rangle \\
+\left\langle \cos\theta_{31}\right\rangle  & +\left\langle \cos\text{\theta}_{32}\right\rangle  & +\left\langle \cos\text{\theta}_{33}\right\rangle  & +... & +\left\langle \cos\text{\theta}_{3N_{b}}\right\rangle \\
+... & +... & +... & +... & +...\\
+\left\langle \cos\theta_{N_{b}1}\right\rangle  & +\left\langle \cos\text{\theta}_{N_{b}2}\right\rangle  & +\left\langle \cos\theta_{N_{b}3}\right\rangle  & +... & +\left\langle \cos\text{\theta}_{N_{b}N_{b}}\right\rangle
\end{array}\right\}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In more compact notation we can write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle =\ell^{2}\overset{N_{b}}{\underset{i,j=1}{\sum}}\left\langle \cos\theta_{ij}\right\rangle
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we have reduced the problem to figuring out what the values of
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cos\theta_{ij}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are in the system.
 This requires a specific model of how the bonds are joined to one another.
 In the following sections we consider two specific models (the freely jointed
 and freely rotating models), and a general model where the bond rotation
 angles are constrained.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Freely Jointed Chain Model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Freely-Jointed-Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest (and most unrealistic) model of chain dimensions is the freely
 jointed chain model, where all bond orientations are equally likely.
 In the freely jointed chain model
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cos\theta_{ij}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $i\ne j$
\end_inset

, because orientations giving positive and negative values of
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 are equally likely.
 The only exception is for the
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

 diagonal terms for which
\begin_inset Formula $i=j$
\end_inset

.
 These represent the projection of a vector onto itself, and all have
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta=1$
\end_inset

.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle =N_{b}\ell^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Freely Rotating Chain Model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Freely-Rotating-Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this model, bond angles are fixed, but rotation about bonds is possible.
 Rotation about a bond sweeps out a cone as shown below.
 The bond rotation angle is defined as
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, and in the freely rotating model all values of
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 are assumed to be equally likely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Free Rotating Chain Model.svg
	width 60text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Freely Rotating Chain Models with views perpendicular to the axis of the
 rotating bond and along the axis of the rotating bond
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the freely rotating chain model, the angle between adjacent bonds is
 fixed at certain angle, referred to here simply as
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 (without the subscripts).
 Adjacent bonds,
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 those with
\begin_inset Formula $i-j=1$
\end_inset

 or
\begin_inset Formula $i-j=-1$
\end_inset

, have
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cos\theta_{ij}\right\rangle =\cos\theta$
\end_inset

.
 It can be shown that terms with
\begin_inset Formula $i-j$
\end_inset

=2 or -2 have
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cos\theta_{ij}\right\rangle =\cos^{2}\theta$
\end_inset

, terms with
\begin_inset Formula $i-j$
\end_inset

=3 or -3 have
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cos\theta_{ij}\right\rangle =\cos\theta$
\end_inset

, etc.
 The matrix of terms making up the summation to give
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 therefore has the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle =\ell^{2}\left\{ \begin{array}{ccccc}
1 & +\cos\theta & +\cos^{2}\theta & +... & +\cos^{(N_{b}-1)}\theta\\
+\cos\theta & +1 & +\cos\theta & +... & +\cos^{(N_{b}-2)}\theta\\
+\cos^{2}\theta & +\cos\theta & +1 & +... & +\cos^{(N_{b}-3)}\theta\\
+... & +... & +... & +... & +...\\
+\cos^{(N_{b}-1)}\theta & +\cos^{(N_{b}-2)}\theta & +\cos^{(N_{b}-3)}\text{\theta} & +... & +1
\end{array}\right\}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of the
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}^{2}$
\end_inset

 terms in the summation,
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

 terms (the diagonal terms with
\begin_inset Formula $i=j$
\end_inset

) are equal to 1.
 There are
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}-1$
\end_inset

 terms with
\begin_inset Formula $i-j$
\end_inset

=1, and an additional
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

-1 terms with
\begin_inset Formula $i-j$
\end_inset

=-1.
 There are therefore 2(
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

-1) terms with a magnitude equal to
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\text{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, there are 2(
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

 -2) terms equal to
\begin_inset Formula $\cos{}^{2}\text{\theta}$
\end_inset

, 2(
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

 -3) terms equal to
\begin_inset Formula $\cos{}^{3}\text{\theta}$
\end_inset

, etc.
 The expression for
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 can therefore be written as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\[
\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle =\ell^{2}\left\{ N_{b}+2(N_{b}-1)\cos\theta+2(N_{b}-2)(\cos\theta)^{2}+...+2\left(\cos\theta\right)^{N_{b}-1}\right\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the more compact notation, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle =N_{b}\ell^{2}+\ell^{2}\overset{N_{b}-1}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}2\left(N_{b}-i\right)\left(\cos\theta\right)^{i}\label{eq:freely rotating - exact}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:freely rotating - exact"

\end_inset

 is an exact expression that is valid for any value of
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Unfortunately, it's not a very useful equation.
 Fortunately, we can get a greatly simplified expression that is very nearly
 exact for any reasonably large value of
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 We are able to do this because
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta$
\end_inset

 is less than one, so that
\begin_inset Formula $(\cos\theta)^{i}$
\end_inset

 rapidly decreases as
\emph on
i
\emph default
 increases.
 For example, for
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=71^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 (the value corresponding to C-C single bonds),
\begin_inset Formula $(\cosÎ¸)^{i}$
\end_inset

 =
\begin_inset Formula $1.3x10^{-5}$
\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $i=10$
\end_inset

.
 For large values of
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

, we only need to consider contributions from values of i which are much
 smaller than
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 A very good approximation is obtained by substituting
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}-i$
\end_inset

 and extending the sum to
\begin_inset Formula $i=\infty$
\end_inset

, which leads to the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle =N_{b}\text{â„“}^{2}\left\{ 1+2\underset{i=1}{\overset{\infty}{\sum}}\left(\cos\theta\right)^{i}\right\}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this point we are in a position to use the following standard sum, valid
 for any value of
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with an absolute magnitude less than 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\overset{\infty}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}x^{i}=\frac{x}{1-x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use of this expression with
\begin_inset Formula $x=\cos\theta$
\end_inset

 gives (after a little algebraic rearrangement):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle =N_{b}\ell^{2}\left\{ \frac{1+\cos\theta}{1-\cos\theta}\right\} \label{eq:freely rotating R2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For singly bonded carbon along the backbone,
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=71^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle =2N_{b}\ell^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

