\begin_layout Standard
The two dimensional stress state is illustrated below in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2d stress state"

\end_inset

.
 In two dimensions there are 3 independent components of the stress tensor.
 Two of these are normal forces where the stress is perpendicular to the
 relevant surface.
 These are
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xx}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{yy}$
\end_inset

, with forces acting in the x and y directions, respectively.
 There is also a shear stress,
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}$
\end_inset

, which act parallel to each of the 4 surfaces of a square chunk of material.
 Note that the magnitudes of the shear forces acting on the 4 different
 surfaces are all equal to one another, a fact imposed by the requirement
 that there must be no net force or torques acting on this overall square
 of material (otherwise the material would be accelerating in response to
 this net force).
 The values of these three stress components depend on the way we define
 the orientation of the coordinate system.
 It is always possible to define a coordinate system so that the shear component
s disappear, and we are only left with normal stresses.
 These are the
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
principal stresses
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Principal stresses
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which in two dimensions are
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}^{p}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{2}^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 The same holds for a 3-dimensional stress state: we can always find a coordinat
e system for any given stress state so that only normal stresses.
 In three dimensions we have three principal stresses,
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}^{p}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{2}^{p}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{3}^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 These act in the three, mutually perpendicular principal stress directions
 as illustrated in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:princial stresses in 3d"

\end_inset

.
 In summary, any state of stress is completely specified by the three principal
 stresses (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}^{p}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{2}^{p}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{3}^{p}$
\end_inset

), and the orientation of the coordinate system used to define these principal
 stresses.
