\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{eng}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{eng}=\frac{P_{z}}{A_{0}}=\frac{d}{d\lambda_{z}}\left(\frac{\Delta F_{d}}{V_{0}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{0}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 are the cross sectional area, length and volume of the undeformed material.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The deformation free energy normalized by the undeformed volume is the deformati
on free energy density,
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{d}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{d}=\frac{\Delta F_{d}}{V_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With these definitions the following simple expression gives the engineering
 stress in terms of the deformation free energy density, for uniaxial deformatio
n along the z axis:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{eng}=\frac{d}{d\lambda_{z}}(\Delta f_{d})\label{eq:tensile stress from strain energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Simple Shear
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a simple shear deformation, two parallel surfaces within a material remain
 at a fixed separation as they slide past one another, as illustrated in
 Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:shear schematic"

\end_inset

.
 In this example an applied shear force,
\begin_inset Formula $P_{xy}$
\end_inset

 is applied to the two surfaces, which each have an area,
\begin_inset Formula $A.$
\end_inset

 The separation between the two surfaces is
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, and the relative displacement of the two surfaces is
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 For these quantities we obtain the shear sress,
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}$
\end_inset

, the engineering shear strain,
\begin_inset Formula $e_{xy}$
\end_inset

 or
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, and the shear modulus,
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Shear stress
\end_layout

\end_inset

Shear stress:
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}=P_{xy}/A,$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{yz}=\sigma_{xz}=0$
\end_inset

 units: N/m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

 (Pascal)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Shear strain
\end_layout

\end_inset

Shear strain:
\begin_inset Formula $e_{xy}=\gamma=u/d$
\end_inset

 units: Dimensionless
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Shear modulus
\end_layout

\end_inset

Shear modulus:
\begin_inset Formula $G\equiv\sigma_{xy}/\gamma$
\end_inset

 (defined in the low-strain regime).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that
\begin_inset Formula $e_{xy}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 are both commonly used symbols to represent the shear strain.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Shear Deformation.svg
	width 30text%

\end_inset


