name "fig:shear schematic"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The force is again given by the derivative of the free energy with respect
 to the displacement in the direction of the applied force:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
P_{xy}=\frac{d(\Delta F_{d})}{du}=\frac{d(\Delta F_{d})}{d\gamma}\frac{d\gamma}{du}=\frac{1}{h}\frac{d}{d\gamma}\left(\Delta F_{d}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The shear stress is then obtained by dividing by the cross-sectional area
 (note:
\begin_inset Formula $hA=V$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $v_{s}$
\end_inset

 =
\begin_inset Formula $n_{s}$
\end_inset

/V,
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}$
\end_inset

 =
\begin_inset Formula $P_{xy}/A$
\end_inset

 :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}=\frac{d}{\partial d\gamma}\left(\Delta f_{d}\right)\label{eq:shear stress from strain energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One complicating factor of simple shear in comparison to uniaxial extension
 or compression is that the strain ellipsoid is rotated continuously during
 the shear experiment.
 As a result we cannot connect the principal axes of the coordinate system
 in a straightforward way.
 The situation for shear in the x-y plane is illustrated in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:simple shear principal extensions"

\end_inset

.
 Shear is a two-dimensional stress state, so the material is undeformed
 in the third direction, in this case the z direction, so
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{z}=1.$
\end_inset

 The principal strains in the x-y plane are
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 While the relationship between the orientation of the strain ellipsoid
 is a complicated one, the shear strain itself is given by the difference
 between
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\gamma=e_{xy}=\lambda_{1}-\lambda_{2}\label{eq:simple shear extension ratios}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:simple shear extension ratios"

\end_inset

 will enable us to determine the deformation free energy of a material undergoin
g a shear deformation, and is used below in Section
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:shear deformation of an elastomer"

\end_inset

.
