\begin_layout Subsubsection
Torsion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important geometry for characterizing soft materials is the torsional
 geometry shown in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:shear in torsion"

\end_inset

.
 In this material a cylindrical or disk-shaped material is twisted about
 an axis of symmetry.
 The material could be a long, thin fiber (Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:shear in torsion"

\end_inset

a) or a flat disk sandwiched between two plates (Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:shear in torsion"

\end_inset

b).
 We obtain the shear modulus by looking at the torsional stiffness of mateiral,

\begin_inset Formula $i.e.$
\end_inset

, the Torque,
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 required to rotate the top and bottom of the fiber by an angle
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/shear in torsion.svg
	width 20col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
