name "fig:shear in torsion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define a cylindrical system with a z axis along the fiber axis.
 The other axes in this coordinate system are the distance
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 from this axis of symmetry, and the angle
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 around the z axis.
 The shear strain in the
\begin_inset Formula $\theta-z$
\end_inset

 plane depends only on
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
e_{\theta z}=r\frac{d\theta}{dz}=r\frac{\theta_{0}}{\ell}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The corresponding shear stress is obtained by multiplying by the shear modulus,

\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\theta z}=Gr\theta_{0}/\ell
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We integrate the shear stress to give the torque,
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
T={\displaystyle \int_{0}^{d/2}r\sigma_{\theta z}2\pi rdr=\frac{\pi G\theta_{0}d^{4}}{32\ell}}\label{eq:fiber stiffness}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This geometry is commonly used in an oscillatory mode, where
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is oscillated at a specified frequency.
 In this case the torque response is obtained by using the dynamic shear
 moduli defined in Section
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Dynamic-Moduli"

\end_inset

 in place of
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.

\end_layout

