\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Free energy change due to deformation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Free Energy Change from Deformation.svg
	width 60text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Contrasting free energies before and after deformation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
What really matters when determining the mechanical properties of a material
 is the change in free energy resulting from a deformation, which we express
 in terms of the molecular extension ratios in the x, y and z directions.
 Prior to deformation, we have
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{R}=R_{x}\hat{x}+R_{y}\hat{y}+R_{z}\hat{z}$
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}=R_{x}^{2}+R_{y}^{2}+R_{z}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The undeformed free energy,
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0},$
\end_inset

 is given by using this expression for
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:deformation free energy"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
F_{0}=-k_{B}T\ln C+\frac{3k_{B}T}{2Na^{2}}\left\{ R_{x}^{2}+R_{y}^{2}+R_{z}^{2}\right\}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
After deformation, the values of
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $R_{y}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $R_{z}$
\end_inset

 are each multiplied by the respective extension ratio (
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{R}=\lambda_{x}R_{x}\hat{x}+\lambda_{y}R_{y}\hat{y}+\lambda_{z}R_{z}\hat{z}$
\end_inset

), so that
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}=\lambda_{x}^{2}R_{x}^{2}+\lambda_{y}^{2}R_{y}^{2}+\lambda_{z}^{2}R_{z}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The deformed free energy,
\begin_inset Formula $F_{def}$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
F_{def}=-k_{B}T\ln C+\frac{3k_{B}T}{2Na^{2}}\left\{ \lambda_{x}^{2}R_{x}^{2}+\lambda_{y}^{2}R_{y}^{2}+\lambda_{z}^{2}R_{z}^{2}\right\}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The free energy change due to deformation of the molecule is given as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta F_{d}=F_{def}-F_{0}=\frac{3k_{B}T\left\{ (\lambda_{x}^{2}-1)R_{x}^{2}+(\lambda_{y}^{2}-1)R_{y}^{2}+(\lambda_{z}^{2}-1)R_{z}^{2}\right\} }{2Na^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result is for the deformation of a single polymer molecule, which for
 a crosslinked elastomer corresponds to a segment that connects crosslink
 points.
 There are a huge number of these segments in a macroscopic chunk of rubber.
 To get the free energy change for the material as a whole, we need to replace

\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula $n_{s}\left\langle R_{x}^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula $n_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the total number of nework strands and
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R_{x}^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is the average value of
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

 for these segments.
 We need to make similar substitutions for
\begin_inset Formula $R_{y}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $R_{z}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta F_{d}=\frac{3k_{B}Tn_{s}\left\{ (\lambda_{x}^{2}-1)\left\langle R_{x}^{2}\right\rangle +(\lambda_{y}^{2}-1)\left\langle R_{y}^{2}\right\rangle +(\lambda_{z}^{2}-1)\left\langle R_{z}^{2}\right\rangle \right\} }{2Na^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we assume that the material was isotropic when it was crosslinked, so
 that
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R_{x}^{2}\right\rangle =\left\langle R_{y}^{2}\right\rangle =\left\langle R_{z}^{2}\right\rangle =\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle /3$
\end_inset

.
 With this assumption, and with
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}^{2}-Na^{2}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the following result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta F_{d}=\frac{k_{B}Tn_{s}\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle \left\{ \lambda_{x}^{2}+\lambda_{y}^{2}+\lambda_{z}^{2}-3\right\} }{2R_{0}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is the mean square end-to-end distance of the polymer strands that span
 the crosslinks, and that
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the value of
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 when the polymer strands obey random walk statistics.
 The relationship between these two quantities depends on the conditions
 of the crosslinking reaction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is often useful to work in terms of intensive free energy changes (free
 energy per unit volume).
 The free energy of deformation per unit volume
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{d}$
\end_inset

 is obtained very simply from
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta F_{d}$
\end_inset

 by dividing by
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, the volume of a sample.
 We retain the same expression as shown above, but with the strand concentration
,
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{s}$
\end_inset

 substituted for the number of strands,
\begin_inset Formula $n_{s}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{d}=\frac{\Delta F_{d}}{V}=\frac{k_{B}Tv_{s}\beta\left\{ \lambda_{x}^{2}+\lambda_{y}^{2}+\lambda_{z}^{2}-3\right\} }{2}\label{eq:Neohookian strain energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{s}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 are defined as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\nu_{s}=\frac{n_{s}}{V};\,\,\beta=\frac{\left\langle R^{2}\right\rangle }{R_{0}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like the intensive free energy, the strand concentration,
\begin_inset Formula $v_{s}$
\end_inset

 is useful because it does not depend on the overall size and shape of the
 elastomer.
 The assumptions used to develop the free energy expression given above
 correspond to the simplest model of rubber elasticity, which is often referred
 to as the Neohookean model
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Neohookean model
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In our discussion of the specific cases of shear and uniaxial deformation
 that we discuss below, we make the additional assumption that the material
 is incompressible, in which case the product of the three principal extension
 ratios is one:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}\lambda_{3}=1\label{eq:incompressibility condition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Shear deformation of an elastomer
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:shear deformation of an elastomer"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For pure shear we need to relate the shear strain,
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, to the extension ratios,
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Pure shear is a two dimensional stress state, with
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{3}$
\end_inset

 = 1 so the Neohookean strain energy function (Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Neohookian strain energy"

\end_inset

) reduces to the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{d}=\frac{k_{B}Tv_{s}\beta\left\{ \lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{2}^{2}-2\right\} }{2}=\frac{k_{B}Tv_{s}\beta(\lambda_{1}-\lambda_{2})^{2}}{2}=\frac{k_{B}Tv_{s}\beta\gamma^{2}}{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The shear stress is obtained by differentiation of the strain energy function
 with respect to
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 (Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shear stress from strain energy"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}=\frac{d}{d\gamma}(\Delta f_{d})=G\gamma
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the shear modulus, given as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G=k_{B}Tv_{s}\beta
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the shear stress is proportional to the shear strain, even for
 large values of the strain.
 The expression for the shear modulus can be used to write the deformation
 free energy density in terms of
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Uniaxial deformation of an elastomer
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Uniaxial-deformation-of-an-elastomer"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For uniaxial extension or compression the deformation is applied along one
 axis, which we define as the z axis.
 We assume that our material is isotropic, so that the extensions in the
 x and z directions are identical to one another, i.e.

\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{x}=\lambda_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, the material is assumed to be incompressible, so
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{x}\lambda_{y}\lambda_{z}$
\end_inset

 = 1.
 We therefore have
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{x}=\lambda_{y}=\lambda_{z}^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 .
 We can therefore write the free energy of a deformed elastomer as a function
 of the single extension ratio,
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{z}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{d}=\frac{G}{2}\left\{ \lambda_{z}^{2}+\frac{2}{\lambda_{z}}-3\right\}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The engineering stress is obtained by differentiating with respect to
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{z}$
\end_inset

 (Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:tensile stress from strain energy"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{eng}=\frac{d}{\partial d\lambda}\left(\Delta f_{d}\right)=G\left\{ \lambda_{z}-\frac{1}{\lambda_{z}^{2}}\right\}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Young's modulus (E) is defined as the derivative of the stress with respect
 to strain, evaluated at low strain (
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{y}=1$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
E\equiv\frac{\partial\sigma_{eng}}{\partial\lambda_{z}}|_{\lambda_{z}=1}=G\left.\left\{ 1+\frac{2}{\lambda_{z}^{2}}\right\} \right|_{\lambda_{z}=1}=3G=3v_{s}\beta k_{B}T,
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The concentration of network strands (
\begin_inset Formula $v_{s}$
\end_inset

) is the inverse of the volume per strand.
 This can be calculated from the molecular weight and density.
 Defining
\begin_inset Formula $M_{s}$
\end_inset

 as the number average molecular weight of a network strand (molecular weight
 between crosslinks) gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
v_{s}\mathrm{\left(\frac{strands}{volume}\right)}=\frac{\rho\left(\mathrm{mass/volume}\right)}{M_{s}\left(\mathrm{mass/mole}\right)}\cdot N_{av}\left(\mathrm{strands/mole}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula $N_{av}$
\end_inset

 is Avogadro's number
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Avogadro's number
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $6.02x10^{23}$
\end_inset

).
 With
\begin_inset Formula $R=k_{B}N_{av}=8.314\,\mathrm{J/mole\cdot K}$
\end_inset

 the expression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\[
E=\frac{3\rho\beta RT}{M_{s}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, note that 1 J/m
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

 = 1 Pa.
 Stresses and elastic moduli have units of force/area or energy/volume.
\end_layout

