\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Calculate the expected value of Young's modulus for a crosslinked polyisoprene
 that has a number average molecular between crosslinks of 4000 g/mole.
 The density of polyisoprene is 0.9 g/cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that the polymer was crosslinked under equilibrium conditions in
 the melt state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Because the polymer was crosslinked under equilibrium conditions, the network
 strands obey random walk statistics, with
\begin_inset Formula ${\color{blue}\beta}$
\end_inset

 = 1.
 To keep everything in SI units, we need the density in units of kg/m
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

 (1 g/
\begin_inset Formula $cm^{3}$
\end_inset

 = 1000 kg/
\begin_inset Formula $m^{3}$
\end_inset

), and
\begin_inset Formula $M_{s}$
\end_inset

 in kg/mole.
 In our example,
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 = 900 kg/
\begin_inset Formula $m^{3}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $M_{s}$
\end_inset

 = 4 kg/mole.
 We'll also assume that we are interested in the elastic modulus near room
 temperature (T
\begin_inset Formula $\thickapprox$
\end_inset

 300 K).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\[
E=\mathrm{\frac{3(900\,kg/m^{3})(8.314J/mole-K)(300K)}{4kg/mole}=1.6x10^{6}\,J/m^{3}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


