\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{G}{G_{0}}=\frac{v_{s}<R^{2}>}{v_{s_{0}}R_{dry}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{v_{s}}{v_{s_{0}}}=\phi_{p}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{<R^{2}>}{R_{0}^{2}}=\phi_{p}^{-2/3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strand concentration,
\begin_inset Formula $v_{s}$
\end_inset

, is proportional to the polymer volume fraction,
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{p}$
\end_inset

, simply because the total amount of polymer for a fixed total volume is
 proportional to
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 We assume that the gel swells affinely, which means that the increase in
 the cube of the chain dimension (i.e., the rms end-to-end distance,
\begin_inset Formula $<R^{2}>^{1/2}$
\end_inset

 is the same as the increase in the overall sample volume.
 For this reason we have
\begin_inset Formula $<R^{2}>^{1/2}=R_{dry}\phi_{p}^{-1/3}$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset Formula $<R^{2}>=R_{dry}\phi_{p}^{-2/3}$
\end_inset

.
 Combination of all three equations above gives the following simple result
 for the shear modulus, G:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G=G_{0}\phi_{p}^{1/3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Shear modulus of a Swollen Elastomer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The example from the previous page illustrates the use of a more Page 283
 general expression for the modulus of an elastomer that has been swollen
 with a solvent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G=v_{s}k_{B}T\frac{<R^{2}>}{R_{0}^{2}}
