\begin_layout Subsection
Relaxation Modulus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The linear (small strain) properties of viscoelastic materials are described
 by the same set of moduli used to describe elastic materials (Young's modulus,
 shear modulus, Poisson's ratio).
 For viscoelastic materials, however, all of these properties time dependent.
 Here we illustrate the relevant concepts for a shear geometry, in which
 case we are interested in the shear relaxation modulus,
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This quantity is defined as a ratio of shear stress to shear strain, in
 the same way that the time-independent elastic shear modulus is defined.
 In this case, however, the shear stress is not constant but depends on
 the time.
 The formal definition is illustrated by considering the instantaneous applicati
on of a shear strain,
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}$
\end_inset

, to a material as illustrated in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:shear strain - instantaneous"

\end_inset

.
 The shear relaxation modulus is defined as the ratio of the resulting time
 dependent stress to this initial strain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G\left(t\right)\equiv\frac{\sigma_{xy}\left(t\right)}{\gamma_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The shear modulus is independent of
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}$
\end_inset

, provided that
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently small.
 This low strain regime, referred to as the linear viscoelastic regime is
 the focus of our remaining discussion of viscoelasticity.

\end_layout

