\begin_layout Subsection
Boltzmann Superposition Principle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the linear viscoelastic regime the effects of strains applied at different
 times are additive, a concept known as the
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Boltzmann superposition principle
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Boltzmann superposition principle
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A simple example is illustrated in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:viscoelasticity - step strains"

\end_inset

, where the following step strains are applied to the sample:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A strain of
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 applied at time
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A strain of
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 applied at time
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A strain of
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\gamma_{3}$
\end_inset

 applied at time
\begin_inset Formula $t_{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/boltzmann_superposition.eps
	width 45text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Material response to a series of step strains.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:viscoelasticity - step strains"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The stress contribution from these different strains is obtained by multiplying
 by the shear relaxation modulus, evaluated at the time that has passed
 since the strain was applied.
 If strain was applied at
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

, for example, the stress at some later time,
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, is obtained by multiplying by
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(t-t_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Adding up the contributions from the three different step strains in our
 example leads to the following::
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}=\Delta\gamma_{1}G(t-t_{1})+\Delta\gamma_{2}G(t-t_{2})+\Delta\gamma_{3}G(t-t_{3})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression can easily be extended to include an arbitrary number of
 step strains:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}=\underset{i}{\sum}\Delta\gamma_{i}G(t-t_{i})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By taking a sum of very small strain increments, we can generalize this
 expression to account for a continuously changing strain.
 We begin by writing
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta\gamma_{i}=\frac{d\gamma}{dt}(t_{i})\Delta t_{i}=\dot{\gamma}(t_{i})\Delta t_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This substitution leads to the following expression for the stress:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}=\underset{i}{\sum}\dot{\gamma}(t_{i})G(t-t_{i})\Delta t_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can write this in integral form by taking
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t_{i}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and replacing the summation by an integral over all times less than the
 current time:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}(t)=\overset{t}{\underset{-\infty}{\int}}\dot{\gamma}(t_{i})G(t-t_{i})dt_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression gives the current stress that remains as a result of all
 of the strains introduced at different times in the past.
 It is often convenient to change variables so that
\begin_inset Formula $s=t-t_{i}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $dt_{i}=-ds$
\end_inset

.
 Note that s =
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 when
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}=-\infty$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset

 when
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}=t$
\end_inset

.
 The integral can therefore be rewritten as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}(t)=\overset{\infty}{\underset{0}{\int}}\dot{\gamma}(t-s)G(s)ds\label{eq:boltzmann superposition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that because
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 represents time,
\begin_inset Formula $G(s)$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $G(t)$
\end_inset

 represent the same time-dependent relaxation modulus.
 We are just using different variables (
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) to represent time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest application of Eq.
 is 'steady shear', where a constant strain rate is applied.
 Because
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is independent of time in this case, it can be brought outside the integral,
 giving the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}=\dot{\gamma}\overset{\infty}{\underset{0}{\int}}G(t)dt
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following expression is obtained for the viscosity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\eta_{0}=\frac{\sigma_{xy}}{\dot{\gamma}}=\overset{\infty}{\underset{0}{\int}}G(t)dt\label{eq:zero shear viscosity - time domain}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We refer to this viscosity as the
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
zero shear viscosity
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Zero shear viscosity
\end_layout

\end_inset

, because it assumes that the material is in the linear viscoelastic regime,
 where the applied stress is low enough so that the stress is proportional
 to the magnitude of the applied strain.
 The subscript '0' is a reminder to us that the zero shear viscosity corresponds
 to a limiting value of the viscosity that is obtained at a very low strain
 rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Idealized Relaxation Curves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One thing to keep in mind when looking at the viscoelastic properties of
 materials is that processes occur over a very large range of time scales.
 To capture all of these time scales we typically plot the time on a logarithmic
 scale.
 The same is true for the frequency-domain experiments discussed below.
 The relaxation modulus can often vary of several orders of magnitude, so
 that we also plot the relaxation modulus itself on a logarithmic scale.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three different idealized forms of the relaxation modulus are shown in Figure

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:relaxation modulus examples"

\end_inset

.
 The simplest behavior corresponds to a
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Maxwell model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Maxwell model
\end_layout

\end_inset

, where a single relaxation time,
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{g}$
\end_inset

, describes the decay in the modulus from the glassy value of
\begin_inset Formula $G_{g}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G\left(t\right)=G_{g}\exp\left(-t/\tau_{g}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This relaxation time could, for example, describe the decay in the modulus
 from a glassy value of
\begin_inset Formula $\approx10^{9}$
\end_inset

 Pa.
 This relaxation time can be viewed as a 'glass transition time', and its
 existence is a clue that some equivalence between time and temperature
 must exist.
 The relaxation time characterizing the glass transition depends very strongly
 on the temperature, but is independent of the polymer molecular weight.
 If the polymer molecular weight is very high, however, the polymers become
 entangled with one another, and behave elastically for times that are too
 short for these entanglements (shown schematically in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:entanglement schematic"

\end_inset

) to relax by molecular diffusion.
 In addition to
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{g}$
\end_inset

, there is a second transition time,
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{e}$
\end_inset

, determined by the lifetime of these molecular entanglements.
 Addition of this second relaxation results in the following expression
 for the relaxation modulus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G\left(t\right)=G_{g}\exp\left(-t/\tau_{g}\right)+G_{e}\exp\left(-t/\tau_{e}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here
\begin_inset Formula $G_{e}$
\end_inset

 is the plateau modulus (often referred to as
\begin_inset Formula $G_{N}^{0}$
\end_inset

 in the literature).
 Entanglements
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Entanglements
\end_layout

\end_inset

 behave like crosslinks, but they have finite lifetimes as the molecules
 diffuse and the entanglements are eliminated and reformed elsewhere.
 The plateau modulus is given by the concentration of entanglements,
\begin_inset Formula $v_{e}$
\end_inset

, or equivalently, by the number average molecular weight between entanglements,

\begin_inset Formula $M_{e}$
\end_inset

 (referred to as the entanglement molecular weight):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G_{e}=v_{e}k_{B}T=\frac{\rho RT}{M_{e}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

