\begin_layout Standard
The actual relaxation behavior of polymeric materials is complex, and can
 generally not be described in detail by including only one or two relaxation
 times.
 The actual relaxation behavior can always be described with sufficient
 accuracy by a
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
generalized Maxwell model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Maxwell model - Generalized
\end_layout

\end_inset

, where we include a large number of individual exponential relaxation processes
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G(t)=\overset{N_{r}}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}G_{i}\exp(-t/\tau_{i})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inclusion of a sufficiently large number of relaxation processes (large

\begin_inset Formula $N_{r}$
\end_inset

) enables very complicated relaxation behavior to be modeled accurately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Temperature Dependence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A characteristic of single-component polymeric materials is that the temperature
 dependence of all of the different relaxation times is the same.
 The concept is illustrated in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:visco T dep 2 relax times"

\end_inset

, which shows the relaxation modulus at two different temperatures for an
 idealized material with two different relaxation times.
 The relaxation times scale with temperature according to the same temperature
 dependent shift factor,
\begin_inset Formula $a_{T}$
\end_inset

.
 The shift factor is equal to one at a reference temperature,
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ref}$
\end_inset

, and increases as the temperature is decreased.
 Because both relaxation times are multiplied by the same factor, the curve
 is shifted linearly along the logarithmic x axis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Temp Shift.png
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Temperature dependence of a material with two relaxation times.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:visco T dep 2 relax times"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because all of the relaxation times are multiplied by
\begin_inset Formula $a_{T}$
\end_inset

 when the temperature is changed, data obtained at different temperatures
 superpose when plotted as a function of
\begin_inset Formula $t/a_{T}$
\end_inset

.
 As a result the relaxation behavior over a large range of times can be
 obtained by measuring the relaxation spectrum at different times, and shifting
 the data to the reference temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Vogel equation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Vogel equation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is an empirical equation that is often used to describe the temperature
 dependence of the shift factor,
\begin_inset Formula $a_{T}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\log(a_{T})=A+\frac{B}{T-T_{\infty}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The factor A is determined from the requirement that
\begin_inset Formula $a_{T}=1$
\end_inset

 at
\begin_inset Formula $T=T_{ref}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
A=-\frac{B}{T_{ref}-T_{\infty}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relaxation times diverge to
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 at
\begin_inset Formula $T=T_{\infty}$
\end_inset

, which in free volume theory is the temperature at which the free volume
 of the equilibrium liquid goes to zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dynamic Moduli
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Dynamic-Moduli"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Dynamic Mechanical Spectroscopy 2.png
	width 40text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dynamic mechanical spectroscopy.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experimentally, a wide variation in time scales is accessed by oscillating
 or vibrating the sample and measuring the frequency response of the material.
 Consider, for example, an oscillatory shear strain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\gamma_{0}\sin(\omega t)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strain rate is also sinusoidal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\dot{\gamma}(t)=\frac{d\gamma(t)}{dt}=\omega\gamma_{0}\cos(\omega t)=\omega\gamma_{0}\sin(\omega t+\pi/2)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the strain and the strain rate are out of phase by
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

/2 (90
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

).
 This concept of a phase difference is very important in understanding the
 frequency dependent dynamic moduli.
 In this case we use Boltzmann superposition to obtain an expression for
 the stress:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}(t)=\overset{\infty}{\underset{0}{\int}}\dot{\gamma}(t-s)G(s)ds=-\omega\gamma_{0}\overset{\infty}{\underset{0}{\int}}\cos\left\{ \omega(t-s)\right\} G(s)ds
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we make use of the following trigonometric identity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\cos(a-b)=\sin(a)\sin(b)+\cos(a)\cos(b)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can therefore write the time dependent stress in the following way.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}(t)=\gamma_{0}\omega\left[\overset{\infty}{\underset{0}{\int}}G(s)\sin(\omega s)ds\right]\sin(\omega t)+\gamma_{0}\omega\left[\overset{\infty}{\underset{0}{\int}}G(s)\cos(\omega s)ds\right]\cos(\omega t)\label{eq:dynamic mech.  - sinusoidal stress}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 (storage modulus) and
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

 (loss modulus) such that
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 describes the component of the stress that is in phase with the strain
 (the elastic component) and
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

 describes the component of the stress that is in phase with the strain
 rate (the viscous component).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\sigma_{xy}(t)}{\gamma_{0}}=G^{\prime}(\omega)\sin(\omega t)+G^{\prime\prime}(\omega)\cos(\omega t)\label{eq:dynamic mech - G' and G" def.}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By comparing Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dynamic mech.  - sinusoidal stress"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dynamic mech - G' and G\" def."

\end_inset

, we obtain the following for
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
G^{\prime}(\omega)=\omega\overset{\infty}{\underset{0}{\int}}G(t)\sin(\omega t)dt\\
G^{\prime\prime}(\omega)=\omega\overset{\infty}{\underset{0}{\int}}G(t)\cos(\omega t)dt
\end{array}\label{eq:G' and G" in terms of G(t)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In is useful to consider the behavior of
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

 in limiting cases where the system is a perfectly elastic solid with no
 viscous character, and where the material is a Newtonian liquid with no
 elastic character:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Perfectly Elastic System:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case the shear modulus is independent of both time and frequency.
 For
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\left(t\right)=\gamma_{0}\sin\left(\omega t\right)$
\end_inset

 we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}(t)=G\gamma(t)=G\gamma_{0}\sin(\omega t)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing to Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dynamic mech - G' and G\" def."

\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
G^{\prime}=G\\
G^{\prime\prime}=0
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Perfectly Viscous System:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We again have
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\left(t\right)=\gamma_{0}\sin\left(\omega t\right)$
\end_inset

, but this time the shear stress depends only on the strain rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{xy}(t)=\eta\frac{d\gamma(t)}{dt}=\eta\omega\gamma_{0}\cos(\omega t)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing to Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dynamic mech - G' and G\" def."

\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
G^{\prime}=0\\
G^{\prime\prime}\left(\omega\right)=\omega\eta
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Phase Angle and Loss Tangent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as the real and imaginary components of a a complex modulus,

\begin_inset Formula $G^{*}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G^{*}\left(\omega\right)=G^{\prime}\left(\omega\right)+iG^{\prime\prime}\left(\omega\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As with any complex number, we can represent
\begin_inset Formula $G^{*}$
\end_inset

 by its magnitude, which we refer to as
\begin_inset Formula $\left|G^{*}\right|$
\end_inset

 and its phase angle, which we refer to as
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\left|G^{*}\left(\omega\right)\right|=\left\{ \left(G^{\prime}\left(\omega\right)\right)^{2}+\left(G^{\prime\prime}\left(\omega\right)\right)^{2}\right\} ^{1/2}\\
\delta=\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{G^{\prime\prime}\left(\omega\right)}{G^{\prime}\left(\omega\right)}\right)
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The significance of
\begin_inset Formula $\left|G^{*}\right|$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 are illustrated by writing the sinusoidal displacement and the resulting
 stress in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\gamma\left(t\right)}{\gamma_{0}}=\sin(\omega t)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\sigma_{xy}(t)}{\gamma_{0}}=\left|G^{*}\right|\sin(\omega t+\delta)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\left|G^{*}\right|$
\end_inset

gives the ratio of the stress amplitude to the strain amplitude, and
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the phase lag between the stress and strain.
 The following expressions relate
\begin_inset Formula $\left|G^{*}\right|$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
G^{\prime}=\left|G^{*}\right|\cos(\delta)\\
G^{\prime\prime}=\left|G^{*}\right|\sin(\delta)\\
\tan(\delta)=\frac{G^{\prime\prime}}{G^{\prime}}
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Loss tangent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
loss tangent
\end_layout

\end_inset

, tan(
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

), gives the fraction of energy that is dissipated during each cycle.
 It is maximized when the inverse of the frequency corresponds to a characterist
ic relaxation time of the material.
 For a material with two characteristic relaxation times,
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

, tan(
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

) will be maximized at
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=2\pi/\tau_{1}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=2\pi/\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Spring and Dashpot Models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As mentioned above, a generalized Maxwell model, where the time-dependent
 relaxation is described by a sum of exponential relaxations, is often used
 to describe the viscoelastic behavior of soft materials.
 A way of visualizing the effect of different relaxation times is to imagine
 a series of springs (elastic elements) and dashpots (viscous elements)
 that are linked together in some way.
 Because it is easy to visualize the extension of springs in a tensile experimen
t than it is to visualized them in a shear experiment, we consider the time
 dependent behavior of the tensile modulus,
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 (Young's modulus in a traditional, static experiment).
 A single maxwell element (Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Maxwell-model"

\end_inset

) has a spring of modulus
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 in series with a dashpot of viscosity
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, and gives and gives an exponential relaxation with a relaxation time,

\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, given by
\begin_inset Formula $\eta/E$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/maxwell model.svg
	width 30text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Maxwell model.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Maxwell-model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 In a generalized Maxwell the stress is given by the sum of the contributions
 from all the individual Maxwell elements.
 In Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:generalized Maxwell model"

\end_inset

 we include a spring with modulus
\begin_inset Formula $E_{r}$
\end_inset

 that is not in series with a dashpot.
 This represents the 'relaxed' modulus, and describes the stress remaining
 in the system for
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The overall stress after the instantaneous application of a tensile strain,

\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

, is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\sigma}{e}=E_{r}+\sum_{j}E_{j}\exp\left(-t/\tau_{j}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}=\eta_{j}/E_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 In order to obtain
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

 we use Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:G' and G\" in terms of G(t)"

\end_inset

.
 The sine and cosine transforms of an exponential function can be determined
 analytically, and we end up with the following for
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime\prime}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 if
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(t\right)=G_{0}\exp\left(-t/\tau\right)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
G^{\prime}(\omega)=\omega G_{0}\overset{\infty}{\underset{0}{\int}}\exp\left(-t/\tau\right)\sin(\omega t)dt=\frac{G_{0}\omega\tau}{1+\left(\omega\tau\right)^{2}}\\
G^{\prime\prime}(\omega)=\omega G_{0}\overset{\infty}{\underset{0}{\int}}\exp\left(-t/\tau\right)\cos(\omega t)dt=\frac{G_{0}\left(\omega\tau\right)^{2}}{1+\left(\omega\tau\right)^{2}}
\end{array}\label{eq:maxwell model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Note: A MATLAB script that demonstrates the use of the use of MATLAB's
 symbolic algebra capability to determine these integrals is given in Appendix
 1).
 Plots of these values for
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

 are shown in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Maxwell model plots"

\end_inset

.
 Note that for
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=1/\tau$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}=G^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 For
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>1/\tau$
\end_inset

 the material behaves as a liquid, with
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime\prime}>G^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 For angular frequencies above
\begin_inset Formula $1/\tau$
\end_inset

, the opposite is true, and the material has solid-like behavior with
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}>G^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
