\begin_layout Section
Semicrystalline Polymers
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Semicrystalline-Polymers"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many polymers of commercial importance are able to crystallize to a certain
 extent.
 The most widespread crystallizable polymers are polyethylene and isotactic
 polypropylene.
 As we will see, crystallization is never complete, and there is always
 a certain amorphous fraction in any polymer.
 For this reason, many of the concepts which apply to amorphous polymers
 are still valid for semicrystalline polymers.
 For example, semicrystalline polymers are often quite brittle at temperatures
 below the glass transition temperature of the amorphous fraction.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following pages, we introduce some common semicrystalline polymers,
 and discuss their basic structural feature polymers, in addition to kinetic
 issues that are important in their processing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Structural Hierarchy in Semicrystalline Polymers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The structure of semicrystalline polymers is much more complex than the
 structure of amorphous polymers, and our discussion in the following pages
 is not as quantitative as our discussion of the random walk configurations
 of polymer chains in amorphous polymers.
 Instead, we illustrate the features of semicrystalline polymers by considering
 the following basic structural features:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Helices formed by individual polymer molecules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Perfect crystals formed by the lateral packing of these helices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Lamellar crystallites formed by folded helices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Semicrystalline regions formed by stacking of lamellar crystallites
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Spherulitic morphologies formed by radial growth of lamellar crystallites
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Structural Repeat Unit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The molecular structure is an important factor in the ability of a polymeric
 material to crystallize.
 One relevant parameter related to the structure vinyl polymers is the number
 of backbone carbons in the repeating molecular structure.
 We refer to this as the
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
structural repeat unit
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Structural repeat unit
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which is distinct from the
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
monomeric repeat unit
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Monomeric repeat unit
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that is defined in terms of the structure of the monomer itself.
 Polyethylene, example, can be viewed as a repeating string of
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{CH_{2}}$
\end_inset

 units, so there one carbon atom per structural repeat unit, although there
 are two carbon atoms per monomeric repeat unit.
 Tacticity needs to be accounted for as well.
 Isotactic vinyl polymers have two backbone carbon atoms per structural
 repeat, because all non-hydrogen substituent groups are on the same side
 of the molecule.
 Syndiotactic vinyl polymers have four backbone carbon atoms per structural
 repeat, because the substituent groups alternate between different sides
 of the molecule.
\end_layout

