\begin_layout Subsection
Growth of a Lamellar Crystallite
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The overall free energy change (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta F$
\end_inset

) associated with the formation of a small crystallite has two components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A surface energy component, which is always positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A bulk free energy component, which is negative for temperatures below the
 equilibrium melting temperature,
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bulk component can be written in terms of the undercooling (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}^{0}-T)$
\end_inset

 by writing the bulk free energy change per unit volume (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $_{c}$
\end_inset

) in terms of its entropic and enthalpic components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{c}=\Delta h_{c}-T\Delta s_{c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta h_{c}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta s_{c}$
\end_inset

 are the enthalpy and entropy of melting for a perfect crystal, normalized
 by the volume of the crystal.
 We can use the fact that
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{c}=0$
\end_inset

 when
\begin_inset Formula $T=T_{m}^{0}$
\end_inset

 to eliminate
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta s_{c}$
\end_inset

 from the equation and write
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{c}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the enthalpy of melting and the the undercooling
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Undercooling
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T,$
\end_inset

 defined as
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}^{0}-T$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{c}=-\frac{\Delta h_{c}\Delta T}{T_{m}}\label{eq:crystallization free energy vs. undercooling}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that we have used the following sign conventions (as is generally the
 case):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta h_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the enthalpy required to melt the crystal, and is always a positive
 number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
From its definition,
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T$
\end_inset

 is positive whenever the temperature is below the equilibrium melting temperatu
re.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the free energy difference between the crystal and the amorphous material,
 and is negative for temperatures below the equilibrium melting temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The growth of a lamellar crystallite occurs by the addition of molecular
 strands (typically corresponding to the c axis of the cyrstalline structure)
 to the growing crystallite as illustrated in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:crystal growth - lamellar crystallite"

\end_inset

.
 In addition to the
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Secondary Nucleation.svg
	width 60text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Schematic representation of a growing lamellar crystallite.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:crystal growth - lamellar crystallite"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we account for the surface energies associated with the new crystal/amorphous
 interface that is created, the increase in free energy for adding
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 "strands" to the face of a lamellar crystallite is given by the following
 expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta F=2a'\lambda_{c}\gamma_{s}+2na'b'\gamma_{e}+na'b'\lambda_{c}\Delta f_{c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we assume that
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is large we can neglect the term involving
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{s}$
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta F<0$
\end_inset

 when
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{c}<\frac{2\gamma_{e}}{\lambda_{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 With
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{c}$
\end_inset

 given by Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:crystallization free energy vs. undercooling"

\end_inset

, we can rewrite the condition that
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta F<0$
\end_inset

 in the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{c}>\frac{2\gamma_{e}T_{m}^{0}}{\Delta h_{c}\Delta T}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A crystal will grow by the addition of additional strands when this criterion
 is met.
 Thick crystals (high
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{c}$
\end_inset

) are thermodynamically favorable, but thin crystals (low
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{c}$
\end_inset

) are kinetically favorable.
 In this model, the crystal thickness which is actually obtained is the
 lowest, thermodynamically possible value.
 The inequality from the previous page therefore becomes an approximate
 equality:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{c}\thickapprox\frac{2\gamma_{e}T_{m}^{0}}{\Delta h\Delta T}\label{eq:crystal thickness prediction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

