\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Exercise:
\series default
 The room temperature densities of polystyrene and toluene are 1.05
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{g/cm^{3}}$
\end_inset

and 0.87
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{g/cm^{3}}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 What reference volume,
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

, should we use to characterize the thermodynamics of polystyrene solutions
 in toluene? What degrees of polymerization would characterize a solution
 where the polystyrene molecular weight is 100,000 g/mole?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Solution:
\series default
 The obvious reference volume in this case is the volume of a toluene molecule,
 which we take as having N=1.
 This volume is obtained from the density and molecular weight of toluene.
 Toluene (
\begin_inset Formula $C_{6}H_{8}$
\end_inset

) has a molecular weight of 92 g/mole.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula
\[
V_{0}=\mathrm{\left(\frac{92\,g}{mole}\right)\left(\frac{cm^{3}}{0.87\,g}\right)=106\,cm^{3}/mole}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that we have used the molar volume for
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This convention will be followed throughout our discussion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The value of
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 for the polymer molecules will be given by the molecular volume, divided
 by the reference volume:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula
\[
N_{polystyrene}=\mathrm{\left(\frac{100,000\,g}{mole}\right)\left(\frac{cm^{3}}{1.05\,g}\right)\left(\frac{mole}{106\,cm^{3}}\right)}=898
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In our discussion of the thermodynamics of mixtures, we will refer to N
 as the number of "segments", defined in terms of a reference volume as
 described here.
 In some cases this reference volume will correspond to a repeat unit of
 the polymer, but this does not need to be the case in general.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chemical Potentials
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Chemical-Potential"

\end_inset

 and Free Energy of Mixing
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Free-Energy-of-Mixing"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chemical potential
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chemical potential
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of A molecules,
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{a}$
\end_inset

, is defined as the free energy required to add an additional 'A' molecule
 to the system.
 Because all A molecules are equivalent, it is also equal to the free energy
 per A molecule in the system.
 The following expressions are helpful
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
F=n_{a}\mu_{a}+n_{b}\mu_{b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\left.\frac{\partial F}{\partial n_{a}}\right|_{n_{b}}=\mu_{a}\\
\left.\frac{\partial F}{\partial n_{b}}\right|_{n_{a}}=\mu_{b}
\end{array}\label{eq:chemical potential definitions}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivative with respect to
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}$
\end_inset

 is taken with
\begin_inset Formula $n_{b}$
\end_inset

 held constant, and vice versa.
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the total extensive free energy of the system, since it increases as
 the numbers of A and B molecules (
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $n_{b}$
\end_inset

) increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Free Energy Mixture 2.png
	width 35text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Animation of the chemical potential of a molecule
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chemical potentials of A and B molecules of the pure components are
 defined as
\begin_inset Formula $u_{a}^{0}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $u_{b}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The free energy of the two components before mixing is therefore given
 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
F_{unmixed}=n_{a}\mu_{a}^{0}+n_{b}\mu_{b}^{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The free energy of mixing is equal to the difference in the free energies
 of the mixed and unmixed systems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta F_{mix}=F-F_{unmixed}=n_{a}\mu_{a}+n_{b}\mu_{b}-(n_{a}\mu_{a}^{0}+n_{b}\mu_{b}^{0})=n_{a}(\mu_{a}-\mu_{a}^{0})+n_{b}(\mu_{b}-\mu_{b}^{0})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because we are only interested in changes in chemical potentials due to
 mixing, we can set the chemical potentials of the pure, unmixed components
 to zero (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{a}^{0}=\mu_{b}^{0}=0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By defining the chemical potentials of the pure components as zero, we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta F_{mix}=n_{a}\mu_{a}+n_{b}\mu_{b}\label{eq:Delf in terms of mua, mub (general)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Delf in terms of mua, mub (general)"

\end_inset

 is completely general, and valid for mixtures of molecules of any size.
 It's not that useful, however, because we generally don't write down values
 of
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $n_{b}$
\end_inset

 when we want to specify the composition of a multicomponent mixture.
 For mixtures of small molecules (metal alloys, for example), we commonly
 use mole fractions,
\begin_inset Formula $X_{a}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}$
\end_inset

, to specify the composition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
X_{a}=\frac{n_{a}}{n_{a}+n_{b}}\\
X_{b}=\frac{n_{b}}{n_{a}+n_{b}}
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This makes sense for metals because the molar volumes of the different component
s are not that different from one another.
 In polymer systems, however, we are often dealing with systems where the
 components have molar volumes that can differ by orders of magnitude.
 This is the situation if we are interested in the solubility of a high
 molecular weight polymer (which can have a molecular weight of several
 hundred thousand g/mole) in a solvent (which will typically have a molecular
 weight of
\begin_inset Formula $\approx100$
\end_inset

 g/mole).
 Organic solutions are typically specified by the weight fractions of the
 different components.
 In discussions of polymer solution thermodynamics it is more common to
 work in terms of volume fractions of the different components in the systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The concepts in this section can be easily extended to systems with more
 than two components, but we confine ourselves here to binary solutions
 of just two components: A molecules of length
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a}$
\end_inset

 and B molecules of length
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 In our discussion of polymer thermodynamics it is important to keep in
 mind
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

 are not necessarily true degrees of polymerization as defined earlier in
 this text.
 Instead they are obtained by dividing the molar volumes of the different
 components by some reference volume,
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}.$
\end_inset

 For polymer/solvent mixtures this reference volume is typically taken as
 the molar volume of the solvent, and for polymer/polymer mixtures it is
 typically taken as the volume per repeat unit for one of the polymers.
 The total volume,
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and volume fractions,
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}$
\end_inset

 are given by the following expressions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
V=n_{a}N_{a}V_{0}+n_{b}N_{b}V_{0}\label{eq:overall system volume V}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\phi_{a}=\frac{n_{a}N_{a}V_{0}}{V}\\
\phi_{b}=\frac{n_{b}N_{b}V_{0}}{V}
\end{array}\label{eq:phi in terms of n}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The free energy of mixing per unit volume,
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{mix}$
\end_inset

, is obtained from
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta F_{mix}$
\end_inset

 by dividing by the volume of the system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{mix}=\frac{n_{a}\mu_{a}+n_{b}\mu_{b}}{n_{a}N_{a}V_{0}+n_{b}N_{b}V_{0}}=\frac{\mu_{a}\phi_{a}}{N_{a}V_{0}}+\frac{\mu_{b}\phi_{b}}{N_{b}V_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By rearranging the equation at the bottom of the previous page we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{mix}V_{0}=\frac{\mu_{a}\phi_{a}}{N_{a}}+\frac{\mu_{b}\phi_{b}}{N_{b}}\label{eq:delf normalized vs. phi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantities
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{mix}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{a}/N_{a}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{b}/N_{b}$
\end_inset

 all depend on the composition of the material.
 The relationship between these quantities is illustrated by the tangent
 construction shown in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tangent construction"

\end_inset

, where the composition dependence of
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{mix}$
\end_inset

 is plotted as a function of
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}$
\end_inset

 for a hypothetical material.
 For a given composition (denoted
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tangent construction"

\end_inset

), the chemcial potentials are obtained by first drawing a tangent to the
 free energy curve at
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}=\phi_{b}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 The value of
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{a}/N_{a}$
\end_inset

 is determined by extrapolating this tangent line to
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}=0$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{a}/N_{a}$
\end_inset

 is obtained by extrapolating the tangent line to
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}=1.$
\end_inset

 This result is consistent with Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delf normalized vs. phi"

\end_inset

, which shows that normalized free energy of mixing at a certain composition
 is determined by the weighted average of the normalized chemical potentials.
 As a result a straight line drawn between the normalized chemical potentials
 on the left and right axes must hit the free energy curve at
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}=\phi_{b}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fully validate the tangent construction illustrated in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tangent construction"

\end_inset

 we still need to show that the straight line between the chemical potentials
 must be equal to the slope of the free energy curve.
 This can done in formal terms by combining Eqs.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chemical potential definitions"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phi in terms of n"

\end_inset

, which after simplification leads to the following relationship:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial(\Delta f_{mix}V_{0})}{\partial\phi_{b}}=\frac{\mu_{b}}{N_{b}}-\frac{\mu_{a}}{N_{a}}=-\frac{\partial(\Delta f_{mix}V_{0})}{\partial\phi_{a}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fact that the tangent must give the difference between
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{b}/N_{b}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{a}/N_{b}$
\end_inset

 makes sense conceptually, because the only way changing the composition
 by some amount requires that an A segment be replaced by a B segment.
\end_layout

