\begin_layout Subsection
Ideal Entropy of Mixing for Polymers
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Ideal-Entropy-of-Mixing"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For small molecules the ideal free energy of mixing is given by the following
 expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta s_{ideal}V_{0}}{R}=-X_{a}\ln X_{b}-X_{b}\ln X_{b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantity
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ideal}V_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the entropy of mixing per mole of molecules.
 If the molar volumes of the A and B molecules are the same, than we can
 simply replace the mole fractions,
\begin_inset Formula $X_{a}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}$
\end_inset

 with the corresponding volume fractions,
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 The entropy of mixing per molecule is independent of the size of the molecule.
 Therefore, the entropy of mixing per repeat unit is smaller than the entropy
 of mixing per molecule by a factor of
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the degree of polymerization.
 In general, we have the following expression for the ideal free energy
 of mixing per volume for polymers with molar volumes of
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a}V_{0}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}V_{0}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{s_{ideal}V_{0}}{R}=-\frac{\phi_{a}\ln\phi_{a}}{N_{a}}-\frac{\phi_{b}\ln\phi_{b}}{N_{b}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Idealized Enthalpy of Mixing
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Inclusion-of-Enthalpy"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key result is that the entropy of mixing for a given volume is much
 smaller for large molecules than it is for small molecules.
 This result explains why different types of polymers almost never mix with
 one another in the liquid state.
 The driving force for two liquids to mix is normally the entropy of mixing,
 but this driving force is very low for mixtures of very large polymer molecules.
 In fact, the entropy of mixing for polymer mixtures is sometimes negative.
 While the ideal entropy of mixing must be positive, it is very small, and
 can be overwhelmeed by non-ideal contributions to the entropy of mixing
 which can be positive or negative.
 Before discussing these effects, however, we will continue in our derivation
 of the Flory Huggins equation for the free energy of mixing.
 The Flory-Huggins theory combines the ideal free energy of mixing with
 a very simple form for the enthalpy of mixing.
 Unlike the entropy of mixing, the enthalpy of mixing is assumed to be independe
