\begin_layout Standard
In this example, the blue square is placed into an environment where one
 of its four nearest neighbors is blue, and three are red.
 Red-blue contacts have an energy (or enthalpy) of
\begin_inset Formula $E_{ab}$
\end_inset

, red-red contacts have an energy of
\begin_inset Formula $E_{aa}$
\end_inset

, and blue-blue contacts have an energy of
\begin_inset Formula $E_{bb}$
\end_inset

.
 The enthalpy change,
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

H, associated with the removal of the square from a pure blue phase on the
 left (4 blue neighbors) to the mixture on the right (1 blue neighbor and
 3 red neighbors) is therefore given by the following formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta H=3E_{ab}+E_{bb}-4E_{bb}=3(E_{ab}-E_{bb})
\end{equation}

