\begin_layout Standard
How do we calculate the energy of a randomly mixed collection of A and B
 molecules? We begin by assuming that the energy of an A-A contact is
\begin_inset Formula $E_{aa}$
\end_inset

, the energy of an B-B contact is
\begin_inset Formula $E_{bb}$
\end_inset

, and the energy of an A-B contact is
\begin_inset Formula $E_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 Also assume that each molecule
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 nearest neighbors (
\begin_inset Formula $z=4$
\end_inset

 for the 2-dimensional array of squares shown above.) The number of A-B contacts
 in a mixture of
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}$
\end_inset

 A molecules and
\begin_inset Formula $n_{b}$
\end_inset

 B molecules is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
n_{aa}=n_{a}zp_{a}/2\\
n_{bb}=n_{b}zp_{b}/2\\
n_{ab}=n_{a}zp_{b}
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that a nearest neighbor is an A molecule.
 The factor of 2 in the expressions for
\begin_inset Formula $n_{aa}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $n_{bb}$
\end_inset

 is needed to avoid double counting.
 (For example, if
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}$
\end_inset

 =2, there is only one interaction between the two molecules, not 2.) Now
 we invoke the mean field (or random mixing) approximation, which is that

\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}=\phi_{a}$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}=\phi_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain the follwing.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
n_{aa}=n_{a}z\phi_{a}/2\\
n_{bb}=n_{b}z\phi_{b}/2\\
n_{ab}=n_{a}z\phi_{b}
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The energy of the mixed state is obtained by multiplying the numbers of
 different contacts by their energy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
E_{mixed}=E_{aa}n_{aa}+E_{bb}n_{bb}+E_{ab}n_{ab}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitution for
\begin_inset Formula $n_{aa}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $n_{bb}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $n_{ab}$
\end_inset

 gives the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
E_{mixed}=E_{aa}n_{a}z\phi_{a}/2+E_{bb}n_{b}z\phi_{b}/2+E_{ab}n_{a}z\phi_{b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The energy of the unmixed state is obtained in a similar fashion, remembering
 that in this state all A's are surrounded by other A's, and all B's are
 surrounded by other B's:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
E_{unmixed}=E_{aa}n_{a}z/2+E_{bb}n_{b}z/2
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The energy change due to mixing is obtained by subtracting the energy of
 the mixed state from the energy of the mixed state:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta E_{mix}=E_{mixed}-E_{unmixed}=\frac{E_{aa}n_{a}z\phi_{a}}{2}+\frac{E_{bb}n_{b}z\phi_{b}}{2}+E_{ab}n_{a}z\phi_{b}-\frac{E_{aa}n_{a}z}{2}-\frac{E_{bb}n_{b}z}{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression can be further simplified by recalling that
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}$
\end_inset

 =
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}n$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $n_{b}$
\end_inset

 =
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}n$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the total number of molecules (
\begin_inset Formula $n=n_{a}$
\end_inset

 +
\begin_inset Formula $n_{b}$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta E_{mix}=nz\left[\frac{E_{aa}\phi_{a}^{2}}{2}+\frac{E_{bb}\phi_{b}^{2}}{2}+E_{ab}\phi_{a}\phi_{b}-\frac{E_{aa}\phi_{a}}{2}-\frac{E_{bb}\phi_{b}}{2}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After some rearrangement we obtain the following expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta E_{mix}=nz\phi_{a}\phi_{b}[E_{ab}-\frac{E_{aa}+E_{bb}}{2}]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the mixing energy is positive if the energy of a-b contacts is
 larger than the average energy of a-a and b-b contacts.
 Because z,
\begin_inset Formula $E_{aa}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $E_{bb}$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset Formula $E_{ab}$
\end_inset

 are actually not measurable quantities, it is common to lump them together
 into a parameter called the
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chi parameter
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chi parameter
\end_layout

\end_inset

 represented by the Greek letter 'chi':
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\chi\equiv\frac{z}{k_{B}T}\left[E_{ab}-\frac{E_{aa}+E_{bb}}{2}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this definition of
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

, the energy of mixing for A and B molecules (with the same size) is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta H_{mix}=\Delta E_{mix}=RT\chi n\phi_{a}\phi_{b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Strictly speaking, the 'enthalpy' and the 'energy' of a system are not the
 same thing.
 The Gibbs free energy involves the enthalpy, and is the appropriate thermodynam
ic quantity at a fixed temperature and pressure.
 The Helmholtz free energy involves the energy, and is the appropriate thermodyn
amic quantity at fixed temperature and volume.
 For compressible systems the two quantities differ slightly.
 We use the expression from the previous page for the extensive enthalpy
 of mixing, and divide by the volume of the system
\begin_inset Formula $\left(nV_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 to obtain the intensive enthalpy of mixing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta h_{mix}=\frac{\Delta H_{mix}}{nV_{0}}=\frac{RT\chi\phi_{a}\phi_{b}}{v_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Normalizing as we did for the ideal entropy of mixing gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta h_{mix}V_{0}}{RT}=\chi\phi_{a}\phi_{b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Flory-Huggins Free Energy of Mixing
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Flory-Huggins Free Energy of Mixing
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Flory-Huggins-Free-Energy"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most commonly used expression used to describe the free energy of mixing
 for polymer/polymer and polymer/solvent mixtures combines mean-field enthalpy
 of mixing with the ideal combinatorial entropy of mixing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{mix}=\Delta h_{mix}-T\Delta s_{ideal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining these forms for the enthalpy and entropy gives the following expressio
n, referred to as the Flory-Huggins free energy of mixing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta f_{mix}V_{0}}{RT}=\frac{\phi_{a}\ln\phi}{N_{a}}+\frac{\phi_{b}\ln\phi_{b}}{N_{b}}+\chi\phi_{a}\phi_{b}\label{eq:Flory Huggins free energy of mixing}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to recognize that many assumptions went into the derivation
 of this equation, and that they can't possibly all be true.
 Nevertheless, this equation is very commonly used in polymer science, and
 needs to be understood.
 In fact, this equation is often used as a definition for
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

.
 Based on our earlier definition of
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 in terms of energetic parameters, one would expect that it's magnitude
 would decrease as the temperature increases.
 In fact, the actual free energy of mixing can have very different behavior,
 and the free energy of mixing is generally accurately described by the
 Flory- Huggins expression only when
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 is allowed to vary with temperature and composition.
 We begin on the next page by constructing phase diagrams, with the assumption
 that the free energy of mixing is adequately described by a value of
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 that is independent of composition.
 Free energy curves for
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a}=N_{b}=1$
\end_inset

 are shown in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:free energy of mixing - regular solution, small molecules"

\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 ranging from 0 to 4.
 For
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a}=N_{b}=1,$
\end_inset

 the critical value of
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 is equal to 2.
 When
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 is larger than this critical value there will be a region of compositions
 where the free energy curve has a negative curvature in the free energy
 curve.

\end_layout

