\begin_layout Subsection
Chemical Potentials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the
\color blue

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sub:Chemical-Potential"

\end_inset


\color inherit
 of species A is determined by differentiating the extensive free energy
 with respect to the number of A molecules in the system.
 The extensive free energy is obtained by multiplying the free energy density,
 f, by the volume of the system, V.
 For a binary mixture of A and B polymers we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{mix}=\frac{RT}{v_{0}}\left\{ \frac{\phi_{a}\ln\phi_{a}}{N_{a}}+\frac{\phi_{b}\ln\phi_{b}}{N_{b}}+\chi\phi_{a}\phi_{b}\right\} V
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the expressions for
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}$
\end_inset

 (Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phi in terms of n"

\end_inset

) and
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 (Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:overall system volume V"

\end_inset

) we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta F_{mix}}{RT}=\left\{ n_{a}\ln\phi_{a}+n_{b}\ln\phi_{b}+\chi n_{a}N_{a}\phi_{b}\right\}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now in a position to obtain expressions for the chemical potentials
 by differentiating the extensive free energy of mixing.
 We make the usual assumption that the chemical potentials of the pure component
s are equal to zero (activities of the pure components equal to one):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\mu_{a}=\frac{\partial\Delta F_{mix}}{\partial n_{a}}=RT\frac{\partial}{\partial n_{a}}\left(n_{a}\ln\phi_{a}+n_{b}\ln\phi_{b}+\chi n_{a}N_{a}\phi_{b}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this way we obtain the following result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mu_{a}}{RT}=\ln\phi_{a}+\phi_{b}\left(1-\frac{N_{a}}{N_{b}}\right)+\chi N_{a}\phi_{b}^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When discussing polymer/solvent mixtures we replace the 'a' and 'b' subscripts
 with 'p' (for polymer) and 's' (for solvent).
 In addition, we take
\begin_inset Formula $N_{s}$
\end_inset

 = 1.
 Formally,
\begin_inset Formula $N_{p}$
\end_inset

 is the ratio of the polymer volume to the solvent volume.
 With these substitutions, we obtain the following expression for
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{s}$
\end_inset

, the solvent chemical potential, which is valid for all concentrations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mu_{s}}{RT}=\ln(1-\phi_{p})+\phi_{p}\left(1-\frac{1}{N_{p}}\right)+\chi\phi_{p}^{2}\label{eq:flory huggins solvent chemical potential}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Limiting case for high molecular weight polymer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For
\begin_inset Formula $N_{p}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 the solvent chemical potential reduces to
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{s}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mu_{s}^{\infty}}{RT}=\ln(1-\phi_{p})+\phi_{p}+\chi\phi_{p}^{2}\label{eq:flory huggins solvent chemical potential - N infinity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition the critical point from Eqs.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:critical composition"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:critical chi"

\end_inset

 occurs at
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{p}=0$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=0.5.$
\end_inset

 This means that for
\begin_inset Formula $\chi>0.5$
\end_inset

 pure solvent will be in equilibrium with a phase that contains both polymer
 and solvent.
 The polymer volume fraction in this phase is determined from the requirement
 that the solvent chemical potential must be zero.
 In other words, if a chunk of high molecular weight polymer is immersed
 in a solvent, solvent diffuses into the polymer until
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{p}$
\end_inset

 decreases to the point where
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{s}^{\infty}=0.$
\end_inset

 In general, this solution must be solved numerically.
 In Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:solvent chmical potential for infinite N"

\end_inset

 we plot the concentration dependence of
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{s}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=0$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=0.5$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=1$
\end_inset

.
