\begin_layout Subsection
Osmotic Pressure
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Osmotic Pressure
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Osmotic-Pressure"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The concept of osmotic pressure can be illustrated by considering the operation
 of the membrane osmometer illustrated conceptually in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:membrane osmometer"

\end_inset

.
 The device consists of a polymer/solvent mixture that is separated from
 a bath of pure solvent by a membrane that is permeable to solvent but impermeab
le to the polymer.
 The chemical potential of the pure solvent is zero, by definition.
 Because the solvent chemical potential in the polymer/solvent mixture is
 less than zero, there is a driving force for solvent to move into this
 side of the membrane from the pure solvent side.
 Solvent will continue to move into this side of the device until the hydrostati
c pressure generated by the increased depth of the liquid layer provides
 counteracts the driving force associated with the chemical potential balance.
 This pressure is the osmotic pressure, and is obtained by dividing the
 chemical potential difference by the solvent volume:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Pi=-\mu_{s}/V_{s}\label{eq:osmotic pressure definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Osmotic Pressure.svg
	width 65text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Diagram demonstrating the principles of osmotic pressure.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:membrane osmometer"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One important aspect of an osmotic pressure measurement is that it can be
 used to provide a direct measure of the number average molecular weight
 of the polymer.
 Osmotic pressure effects are important in many other situations as well.
 For example, the osmotic pressure is the minimum pressure required to purify
 a solution by forcing it through a membrane.
 The osmotic pressure of aqueous solutions is also important in a wide variety
 of situations in biology.
 The height of many trees is limited by the maximum osmotic pressure that
 can be sustained in the leaves, since this is the driving force that draws
 water to the upper reaches of the tree.
 Here we explore these phenomena in more detail, and develop some quantitative
 descriptions of the osmotic pressure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By combining the Flory-Huggins expression for the solvent chemical potential
 (Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:flory huggins solvent chemical potential"

\end_inset

) with the definition of the osmotic pressure (Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:osmotic pressure definition"

\end_inset

), we obtain the following expression for
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Pi=\frac{RT}{V_{s}}\left(-\ln(1-\phi_{p})-\phi_{p}\left(1-\frac{1}{N_{p}}\right)-\chi\phi_{p}^{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If
\begin_inset Formula $N_{p}$
\end_inset

 is large the osmotic pressure depends only on the polymer concentration,
 and not on the degree of polymerization.
 The following result is obtained for
\begin_inset Formula $N_{p}$
\end_inset

 >>1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Pi=\frac{RT}{V_{s}}\left(-\ln(1-\phi_{p})-\phi_{p}-\chi\phi_{p}^{2}\right)\label{eq:osmotic pressure flory N infinite}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Osmometry for Molecular Weight Determination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number average molecular weight can be obtained by measuring the osmotic
 pressure of a dilute polymer solution.
 Using the dilute solution form of the Flory-Huggins expression for the
 solvent chemical potential (Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:solvent chemical potential - flory dilute solution"

\end_inset

) gives the following for
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Pi}{RT}=\frac{\phi_{p}}{N_{p}V_{s}}+\left(1/2-\chi\right)\frac{\phi_{p}^{2}}{V_{s}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polymer volume fraction and overall solution volume (V) are given by
 the following expressions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\phi_{p}=\frac{n_{p}N_{p}V_{s}}{V}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use of this expression for
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{p}$
\end_inset

 gives the following for
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Pi}{RT}=\frac{n_{p}}{V}+(0.5-\chi)N_{p}^{2}V_{s}\left(\frac{n_{p}}{V}\right)^{2}+...
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here it is helpful to rewrite
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}/V$
\end_inset

 in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{n_{p}}{V}=\left(\frac{w}{V}\right)\left(\frac{n_{p}}{w}\right)=\frac{C}{M_{n}}\label{eq:np/v=c/mn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is simply the polymer concentration (kg/m
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

 in SI units, g/cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

 in the units that are more commonly used) and
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the number average molecular weight (kg/mole in SI units).
 The osmotic pressure is therefore related to the number average molecular
 weight and concentration as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Pi}{RT}=\frac{C}{M_{n}}+(0.5-\chi)N_{p}^{2}V_{s}\left(\frac{1}{M_{n}}\right)^{2}C^{2}+...\label{eq:osmotic pressure dilute solution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is expression is often written as a virial expansion
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Virial expansion
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in powers of the concentration:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Pi}{RT}=\frac{C}{M_{n}}+A_{2}C^{2}+A_{3}C^{3}+...\label{eq:osmotic pressure virial expansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the second virial coefficient
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Second virial coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which describes effective two-body interactions between polymer segments
 within the solvent.

\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 = 0 for
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=0.5$
\end_inset

, which means that the polymer chain does not 'see' itself under these condition
s.
 For
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=0.5$
\end_inset

, the polymer chain behaves as a random walk, with chain dimensions very
 similar to what is obtained for the pure, amorphous polymer in the absence
 of solvent.
 For
\begin_inset Formula $\chi>0.5$
\end_inset

, polymer/polymer contacts are more favorable than polymer/solvent contacts.
 Under these conditions, high molecular weight polymers will not dissolve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Scaling Theory of Osmotic Pressure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous derivation of the expressions for the osmotic pressure are
 useful, but they are not packed with physical insight regarding the actual
 meaning of osmotic pressure.
 Some simple physical arguments are more useful in this sense.
 We can start by making an analogy to the ideal gas law, which must be valid
 in the dilute regime.
 We start with the familiar ideal gas law:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
PV=nRT
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we replace the pressure,
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, with the osmotic pressure,
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

, and replace the number of moles of gas molecules,
\begin_inset Formula $n,$
\end_inset

 with the number of polymer molecules
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 By equating
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}/V$
\end_inset

 with
\begin_inset Formula $C/M_{n}$
\end_inset

 (Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:np/v=c/mn"

\end_inset

), we recover the leading term in virial expansion for the osmotic pressure
 (Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:osmotic pressure virial expansion"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Pi=\frac{CRT}{M_{n}}\label{eq:osmotic pressure - leading term}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the dilute regime, molecular collisions are rare, and the pressure and
 free energy are dominated by the entropic penalty associated with confinement
 of the molecules into a fixed volume.
 Virial coefficients quantify the deviations from this ideal, dilute limit.

\end_layout

