\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
What is the overlap concentration poly(methyl methacrylate) with M = 100,000
 g/mole in toluene?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We can combine Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:overlap concentration"

\end_inset

 for the overlap concentration with Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:R0 for self avoiding walk"

\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
C^{*}=\frac{M}{R_{0}^{3}N_{av}}=\frac{M}{a_{s}^{3}N^{1.8}N_{av}}=\frac{M_{0}}{a_{s}^{3}N^{0.8}N_{av}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that we have used the self-avoiding walk expression for
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}$
\end_inset

, which is the relevant expression for good solvent conditions (
\begin_inset Formula $\chi<0.5).$
\end_inset

 PMMA has
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}$
\end_inset

 = 100 g/mole, so
\begin_inset Formula $N=1000$
\end_inset

 for the polymer in our example.
 With these values of
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}$
\end_inset

, and an assumed value of 7 Ã… (
\begin_inset Formula $7\times10^{-8}$
\end_inset

 cm) for
\begin_inset Formula $a_{s}$
\end_inset

, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}=1.9\times10^{-3}\,\mathrm{g/cm^{-3}}$
\end_inset

.
 The density of toluene is slightly less than 1 g/cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

, so this corresponds to a polymer weight fraction of a couple tenths of
 a percent.

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic assumption of scaling theory of osmotic pressure is that
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 is still given by Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:osmotic pressure vs correlation length"

\end_inset

 at concentrations above the overlap concentration, but that
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 has a different meaning in this regime.
 The approach works in the 'semidilute' solution regime where the overall
 concentration is still low (
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{p}$
\end_inset

 < 0.25), but where there is substantial overlap between polymer molecules.
 Each overlap point represents a constraint that contributes an entropic
 contribution of ~
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

 to the free energy of the system.
 The osmotic pressure is therefore ~
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

 times the concentration of overlap points, or
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T/\xi^{3}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is the correlation length
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Correlation length
\end_layout

\end_inset

, or average distance between overlap points.
 As the solution gets more concentrated, the average distance between polymer
 contacts decreases., as shown schematically in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:correlation length concentration schematic"

\end_inset

.

\end_layout

