\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Diagram of equilibrium swelling
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Work done on system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
(p_{in}-p_{out})dV=\Delta pdV
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Change in elastic free energy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
d(\Delta F_{d})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta p=\frac{\partial}{\partial V}\Delta F_{d}=V\frac{\partial}{\partial V}\Delta f_{d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the specific case of a Neohookean material, we begin with the appropriate
 free energy expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{d}=\frac{G\left\{ \lambda_{x}^{2}+\lambda_{y}^{2}+\lambda_{z}^{2}-3\right\} }{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For isotropic swelling,
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{x}=\lambda_{y}=\lambda_{z}=\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 The shear modulus in this equation is the modulus of the reference state,
 which has V = V0 and
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 = 1.
 With
\begin_inset Formula $V/V_{0}=\lambda^{3}$
\end_inset

 we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta f_{d}=\frac{3G(\lambda^{2}-1)}{2}=\frac{3G}{2}\left[\left(\frac{V}{V_{0}}\right)^{2/3}-1\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The elastic pressure at the reference state is given by differentiating
 with respect to the volume, and evaluating the result at
\begin_inset Formula $V=V_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta p=V_{0}\frac{\partial(\Delta f_{d})}{\partial V}|_{V=V_{0}}=\frac{\partial}{\partial V}\left[\frac{3G}{2}\left(\frac{V}{V_{0}}\right)^{2/3}\right]_{V=V_{0}}=G
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result from the previous page is that the elastic swelling pressure
 is equal to the shear modulus of the material.
 This shear modulus is related to the polymer volume fraction in the swollen
 gel by the expression derived previously.
 In a swelling experiment, the pressure is simply the osmotic pressure differenc
e associated with the difference in polymer concentrations inside and outside
 the gel:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{in}-\Pi_{out}=\frac{f\phi_{p}^{1/3}\rho RT}{M_{s}}\frac{\left\langle R_{dry}^{2}\right\rangle }{R_{0}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

