\begin_layout Standard
The osmotic pressure in a bath of pure solvent is zero (
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{out}$
\end_inset

 = 0).
 If a dry material is immersed in the solvent bath, it takes up solvent,
 reducing
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{p}$
\end_inset

 until the osmotic pressure inside the gel is equal to its shear modulus.
 The following equation for
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{p}$
\end_inset

 is obtained if we use the scaling expression for the osmotic pressure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{k_{B}T}{a_{0}^{3}}\phi_{p}^{9/4}=\frac{f\phi_{p}^{1/3}\rho RT}{M_{s}}\frac{<R_{dry}^{2}>}{R_{0}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


