\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Interfacial Free Energy
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Interfacial structure.svg
	width 60text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Schematic representation of the interface between immiscible polymers.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:polymer/polymer interface schematic"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interface between two immiscible polymers is characterized by a finite
 interfacial width,
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 The actual value of
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is determined by a balance of enthalpic considerations, which favor a small
 value of
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, and entropic considerations, which favor a large value of
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 Below we obtain an expression for the interfacial energy as a function
 of
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, and minimize this with respect to
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 to get expressions for both
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and the interfacial free energy between immiscible A and B polymers.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The enthalpic contribution to the interfacial free energy is obtained by
 integrating the enthalpy per unit volume,
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta h$
\end_inset

, associated with contacts between A and B repeat units in the interfacial
 zone.
 Here we use the same regular solution form that forms the basis of the
 Flory-Huggins expression for the free energy of mixing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Delta h(z)=\frac{RT}{V_{0}}\chi\phi_{a}(z)\phi_{b}(z)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we assume as simple linear expression for the concentration profile in
 the interfacial zone, we have the following for
\begin_inset Formula $0<z<w$
\end_inset

 (as illustrated in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:interfacial width concentration profile"

\end_inset

).

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\phi_{a}(z)=1-z/w;
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\phi_{b}(z)=z/w
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Enthalpy.png
	width 35text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Linear approximation to the concentration profile across an interface between
 immiscible polymers
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:interfacial width concentration profile"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These expressions result in the following for
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\chi}$
\end_inset

, the enthalpic contribution to the interfacial free energy.
 We refer to this contribution as
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\chi}$
\end_inset

 because it includes all of the thermodynamic interactions that are included
 in
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

.
 In addition to all the enthalpy of mixing, this parameter also includes
 the non-ideal entropy of mixing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{\chi}=\overset{w}{\underset{0}{\int}}\Delta h\left(z\right)dz=\frac{RT\chi}{V_{0}}\overset{w}{\underset{0}{\int}}\left(\frac{z}{w}\right)\left(1-\frac{z}{w}\right)dz=\frac{RTw\chi}{6V_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simple argument for the entropic contribution every time a random walk
 goes from one side of the interface to the other, it must turn around,
 so that we use one half of the available molecular configurations.
 If the number of molecular configurations is
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, the configurational entropy of associated with these configuration is

\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}\ln\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 If the number of configurations decreases by a factor or 2, then the entropy
 decreases by
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}\ln\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 and the free energy increases by
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T\ln\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Because our theory is already approximate, we'll assume that this free
 energy increase per forced turnaround of a polymer molecule is simply
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our calculation of the entropic contribution to the free energy proceeds
 in the four steps outlined below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Determine
\begin_inset Formula $N_{w}$
\end_inset

, number of repeat units in random walk with
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}=w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $a\sqrt{N_{w}}=w;$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $N_{w}=\left(w/a\right)^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate
\begin_inset Formula $v_{w}$
\end_inset

, the volume of each of these random walks:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $v_{w}=N_{w}v_{0}=v_{0}\left(w/a\right)^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{w}$
\end_inset

, the number of these random walks per unit area in the interfacial region:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{w}=\frac{w}{v_{w}}=\frac{a^{2}}{wv_{0}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
multiply by
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{s}$
\end_inset

, the entropic contribution to the interfacial free energy:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{s}=\frac{k_{B}Ta^{2}}{w}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The overall interfacial free energy,
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ab}$
\end_inset

, is obtained by adding
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\chi}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{s}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ab}=\gamma_{\chi}+\gamma_{s}=\frac{k_{B}T}{v_{0}}\left(\frac{\chi w}{6}+\frac{a^{2}}{w}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The actual value of
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is obtained by minimizing
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 with respect to
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $w=a\sqrt{\frac{6}{\chi}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ab}=\frac{2ak_{B}T}{v_{0}}\sqrt{\chi/6}=\frac{2aRT}{V_{0}}\sqrt{\chi/6}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This approximate approach gives the correct scaling (
\begin_inset Formula $w\propto a\chi^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

;
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ab}\propto\frac{ak_{B}T}{v_{0}}\chi^{1/2}$
\end_inset

), but the exact numerical prefactors are not obtained with quantitative
 accuracy with this approach.
 A more complete treatment results in the following for
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
w=\frac{2a}{\sqrt{6\chi}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{ab}=\frac{aRT}{V_{0}}\sqrt{\chi/6}\label{eq:gamma helfand form}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Block Copolymer Morphologies
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Diblock Copolymer Morphologies
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Block copolymers consisting of two different polymers characterized by a
 sufficiently large value of
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 form a wide variety of interesting morphologies.
 In these cases two different polymer types that prefer to separate into
 different phases are covalently linked to one another along a single molecule.
 The morphologies observed for simple diblock copolymer molecules (a sequence
 of A repeat units linked to a sequence of B repeat units) is shown in Figure

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Diblock-copolymer-morphologies."

\end_inset

.
 If the length of the A block is much longer than the length of the B block,
 then the B blocks segregate into isolated spheres in a continuous matrix
 of A polymer formed from the A blocks.
 If the relative length of the B block is increased, the spheres transition
 to a hexagonal array of cylinders, and then to a morphology where the B
 cylinders form an interconnected, 3-dimensional network within the A matrix.
 If the A and B block lengths are similar in length, then the morphology
 is a simple alternating array of A and B lamellae, as shown schematically
 in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:lamellar diblock copolymer morphology"

\end_inset

.
 An electron micrograph of a lamellar diblock copolymer morphology is shown
 in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:lamellar block copolymer micrograph"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

