\begin_layout Standard
The free energy per molecule of a lamellar-forming diblock copolymer is
 the sum of a chain stretching free energy,
\begin_inset Formula $F_{s}$
\end_inset

 , and a free energy associated with the interface between the A and B domains.
 We refer to this interfacial free energy per chain as
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
 For our purposes we assume that the A and B blocks have the same statistical
 segment length,
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 The overall volume fractions of the two different blocks,
\begin_inset Formula $f_{a}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $f_{b}$
\end_inset

, are given by the relative degrees of polymerization of the two blocks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
f_{a}=\frac{N_{a}}{N_{a}+N_{b}}=\frac{N_{a}}{N}\\
f_{a}=\frac{N_{b}}{N_{a}+N_{b}}=\frac{N_{b}}{N}
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the overall degree of polymerization of the molecule,
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default
,
\begin_inset Formula $N=N_{a}+N_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 The overall width of the A region of the block copolymer is
\begin_inset Formula $f_{a}\ell$
\end_inset

, and the width of the B region is
\begin_inset Formula $f_{b}\ell$
\end_inset

.
 The stretching free energy is obtained from the requirement that each block
 of the molecule must have an rms end-to-end distance equal to half the
 width of the respective region:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
R_{0}^{a}=f_{a}\ell/2\\
R_{0}^{b}=f_{b}\ell/2
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define
\begin_inset Formula $f_{a}$
\end_inset

 and If the degrees of polymerization of the two blocks are
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

, and the statistical segment length for each of the two different repeating
 units is
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
F_{s}=\frac{3}{2}\frac{RT\left(R_{0}^{a}\right)^{2}}{N_{a}a^{2}}+\frac{3}{2}\frac{RT\left(R_{0}^{b}\right)^{2}}{N_{b}a^{2}}=\frac{3}{8}\frac{\ell^{2}}{Na^{2}}\label{eq:lamellar diblock stretching free energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interfacial free energy is obtained by multiplying the interfacial free
 energy by the area per molecule along the A/B interface, which we refer
 to as
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
F_{\gamma}=\gamma_{ab}\Sigma\label{eq:lamellar diblock interfacial free energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This area per molecule is given by dividing the molecular volume,
\begin_inset Formula $NV_{0}$
\end_inset

, by the length per molecule,
\begin_inset Formula $\ell/2$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\Sigma=\frac{2NV_{0}}{\ell}\label{eq:lamellar diblock interfacial area}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The overall free energy per chain,
\begin_inset Formula $F_{tot}$
\end_inset

, is given by the sum of
\begin_inset Formula $F_{s}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
 Combination of Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma helfand form"

\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ab}$
\end_inset

 with Eqs.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lamellar diblock stretching free energy"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lamellar diblock interfacial free energy"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lamellar diblock interfacial area"

\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
F_{tot}=\frac{3}{8}\frac{RT\ell^{2}}{Na^{2}}+\frac{2aNRT}{\ell}\sqrt{\chi/6}\label{eq:lamellar diblock overall free energy expression}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equilibrium value of
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

, which we refer to as
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{eq}$
\end_inset

 is obtained as the value of
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 for which
\begin_inset Formula $F_{tot}$
\end_inset

 is minimized.
 Setting
\begin_inset Formula $dF_{tot}/d_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 to 0 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula
\[
\frac{8a^{3}N^{2}}{3}\sqrt{\chi/6}=\ell^{3}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\ell_{eq}=\left(\frac{8}{3\cdot\sqrt{6}}\right)^{1/3}aN^{2/3}\chi^{1/6}=1.03aN^{2/3}\chi^{1/6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use the fact that
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}=N^{1/2}$
\end_inset

a to write the expression for
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{eq}$
\end_inset

 in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\ell_{eq}}{R_{0}}=1.03\left(\chi N\right)^{1/6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now substitute
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{eq}$
\end_inset

 for
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 in Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lamellar diblock overall free energy expression"

\end_inset

 to obtain the following expression for the equilibrium free energy per
 molecule in the lamellar microstructure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula
\[
F_{tot}=\frac{3}{8}\frac{RT}{Na^{2}}\left(\frac{8}{3\cdot\sqrt{6}}\right)^{2/3}a^{2}N^{4/3}\chi^{1/3}+\left(\frac{8}{3\cdot\sqrt{6}}\right)^{-1/3}\frac{2aNRT}{aN^{2/3}\chi^{1/6}}\sqrt{\chi/6}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula
\[
\frac{F_{tot}}{RT\left(\chi N\right)^{1/3}}=\frac{3}{8}\left(\frac{8}{3\cdot\sqrt{6}}\right)^{2/3}+\left(\frac{8}{3\cdot\sqrt{6}}\right)^{-1/3}\frac{2}{6^{1/2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula
\[
\frac{F_{tot}}{RT\left(\chi N\right)^{1/3}}=\frac{3}{8}\left(\frac{8}{3}\right)^{2/3}6^{-1/3}+2\left(\frac{8}{3}\right)^{-1/3}6^{-1/3}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula
\[
\frac{F_{tot}}{RT\left(\chi N\right)^{1/3}}=3\left(\frac{3}{8\cdot6}\right)^{1/3}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
F_{eq}=1.19RT\left(\chi N\right)^{1/3}\label{eq:molar free energy for lamellar phase}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:molar free energy for lamellar phase"

\end_inset

 gives us the molar free energy for a lamellar phase, but it still does
 not tell us if this lamellar phase has a lower free energy for the disordered
 phase, where the A and B blocks remain completely mixed.
 In order to do this we need to compare to the molar free energy in the
 disordered phase, where the A and B blocks remain completely mixed with
 one another.
 To do this we use the Flory-Huggins free energy of mixing (Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Flory Huggins free energy of mixing"

\end_inset

).
 Because the block copolymer is a one component system, there is no entropy
 of mixing, so we don't include the ideal entropy of mixing terms.
 We just have the term involving
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

, which accounts for the interactions between the A and B repeat units in
 the mixed, disordered phase.
 The free energy per molecule is obtained by multiplying the free energy
 per unit volume by the molecular volume,
\begin_inset Formula $NV_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We get the following simple expression for
\begin_inset Formula $F_{dis}$
\end_inset

, the molar free energy of the disordered phase:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
F_{dis}=RT\chi\phi_{a}\phi_{b}=RT\chi f_{a}f_{b}\label{eq:diblock disordered phase free energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a symmetric diblock copolymer with
\begin_inset Formula $f_{a}=f_{b}=0.5$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $F_{dis}=F_{eq}$
\end_inset

 when
\begin_inset Formula $\chi N$
\end_inset

 is equal to 10.4.
 When
\begin_inset Formula $\chi N$
\end_inset

 is larger than this value, the ordered phase free energy given by Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:molar free energy for lamellar phase"

\end_inset

 is lower than the disordered phase free energy given by Eq.

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:diblock disordered phase free energy"

\end_inset

.
 As a result we expect that an ordered lamellar phase will be formed for

\begin_inset Formula $f_{a}=0.5$
\end_inset

 when
\begin_inset Formula $\chi N$
\end_inset

 is greater than 10.4.
 A disordered phase will be formed for
\begin_inset Formula $\chi N<10.4$
\end_inset

.
 This value of 10.5 is remarkably similar to the value of 10.5 that is obtained
 by a much more detailed calculation.
 These more detailed calculations are necessary in order to understand how
 the preferred geometry of the ordered phase (spheres, cylinders, etc.) depends
 on the
\begin_inset Formula $f_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 A full calculation of the phase diagram is shown in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:block copolymer phase diagram"

\end_inset

