\begin_layout Subsection
Quantifying the Solid/Liquid Transition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The temperature dependence of the mechanical properties of the triblock
 copolymer solutions are quantified by the frequency dependence of the storage
 and loss moduli,
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime\prime}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It is conceptually simpler to think in terms of the time-dependence of
 the relaxation modulus,
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

, which can be written as a sum of exponential relaxations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G\left(t\right)={\displaystyle \sum_{i}G_{i}\exp\left(-t/\tau_{i}\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the frequency domain, the values storage and loss moduli are given by
 the following expressions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G^{\prime}\left(\omega\right)={\displaystyle \sum_{i}\frac{G_{i}\tau_{i}^{2}\omega^{2}}{1+\tau_{i}^{2}\omega^{2}}}\label{eq:G prime with multiple relaxation times}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G^{\prime\prime}\left(\omega\right)={\displaystyle \sum_{i}\frac{G_{i}\tau_{i}\omega}{1+\tau_{i}^{2}\omega^{2}}}\label{eq:G double prime with multiple relaxation times}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most important thing for us is the viscosity, which we can obtain in
 terms of the values of
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

, or in terms of the loss modulus at very low frequencies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\eta={\displaystyle \sum_{i}G_{i}\tau_{i}}{\displaystyle =\lim_{\omega\rightarrow0}\frac{G^{\prime\prime}}{\omega}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We generally obtain data as a master plot (where the frequency is multiplied
 by the temperature shift factor,
\begin_inset Formula $a_{T}$
\end_inset

).
 In this case we obtain the temperature dependence of the viscosity by multiplyi
ng by
\begin_inset Formula $a_{T}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\eta=a_{T}\lim_{a_{T}\omega\rightarrow0}\frac{G^{\prime\prime}}{a_{T}\omega}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also obtain an expression for the limiting modulus at high frequency
 (or low temperature):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G_{0}=\sum_{i}G_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we define an average relaxation time,
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{av}$
\end_inset

 in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\tau_{av}=\frac{\eta}{G_{0}}=\frac{\sum G_{i}\tau_{i}}{\sum G_{i}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

