\begin_layout Subsection
Characterizing the Glass Transition in PMMA domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The glass transition is typically observed as step change in heat flow as
 a sample is cooled through the glass transition.
 In our case the PMMA domains go through a glass transition during cooling,
 but the PMMA concentration is so low that the glass transition is not clearly
 observed during cooling or when when the sample is immediately reheated
 after cooling (see Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:triblock gel DSC curves"

\end_inset

).
 However, a large enthalpy peak is observed after the sample has been left
 to 'age' at room temperature for a long time before reheating the sample.
 As shown in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:triblock gel aging peaks"

\end_inset

, the enthalpy peak gets larger and moves to higher temperature as the aging
 time at room temperature is increased.
 This peak has the appearance of a melting peak associated with crystallization,
 but in this case it arises from the glassy PMMA domains.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The origins of the enthalpy peak observed during the aging experiments can
 be understood by realizing that the glass transition separates an equilibrium,
 liquid regime at temperatures above
\begin_inset Formula $T_{g}$
\end_inset

 from a non-equilibrium, glassy regime at temperatures below
\begin_inset Formula $T_{g}$
\end_inset

.
 At temperatures below the glass transition, the enthalpy content of the
 sample is higher than the equilibrium enthalpy content defined by the extrapola
tion of the liquid behavior (the dashed line in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:triblock gel enthalpy recovery origin"

\end_inset

).
 As a result, the enthalpy slowly decreases toward this equilibrium line
 as the sample is aged below the glass transition.
 The decrease in enthalpy during this aging process is labeled as
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H_{a}$
\end_inset

 in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:triblock gel enthalpy recovery origin"

\end_inset

.
 When the sample is reheated, the enthalpy increases with temperature according
 to the glassy heat capacity,
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{g}$
\end_inset

.
 As a result the enthalpy content eventually crosses the equilibrium line
 and becomes less than the equilibrium enthalpy content.
 At a temperature somewhere just above
\begin_inset Formula $T_{g}$
\end_inset

, the sample is able to equilibrate, and the enthalpy increases by an amount

\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H_{r}$
\end_inset

 in order to catch up to the equilibrium value.
 This is the enthalpy corresponding to the peaks in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:triblock gel aging peaks"

\end_inset

.
 As the aging time decreases,
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H_{a}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H_{r}$
\end_inset

 both decrease, and the temperature at which the enthalpy is recovered moves
 closer to
\begin_inset Formula $T_{g}$
\end_inset

.
 The actual value of the
\begin_inset Formula $T_{g}$
\end_inset

 can be estimated by measuring the area of the enthalpy recovery peak and
 plotting against the location of this peak.
 Doing this for the data shown in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:triblock gel aging peaks"

\end_inset

 results in an estimate for
\begin_inset Formula $T_{g}$
\end_inset

 of the PMMA domains of 35
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

C.

\end_layout

