\begin_layout Subsection
Concentration of the gel Modulus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Elasticity of the triblock copolymer solutions at low temperatures arises
 from the fact that the middle, PnBA blocks of the copolymer can span different
 PMMA aggregates, thereby linking the whole structure together.
 The PMMA aggregates behave as physical crosslinks with a functionality
 given by the number of midblocks that that bridge different aggregates.
 This functionality is obtained by multiplying the aggregation number,
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 the number of PMMA endblocks in a single aggregate, by the probability

\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 that a PnBA midlbock spans two different PMMA aggregates (we also have
 to divide by two to account for the fact that there are two PMMA blocks
 on each triblock copolymer molecule).
 Aggregation numbers depend on the polymer concentration, and are typically
 very large, as illustrated in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:triblock gel aggregation numbers"

\end_inset

.
 For high molecular weight polymers the percolation threshold, where the
 average functionality of a micelle is 2, is quite low, corresponding to

\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{p}\approx0.035.$
\end_inset

 Above this percolation threshold, the shear modulus is given by the following
 expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
G_{0}=\nu k_{B}T\frac{D^{2}}{R_{0}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the average distance between micelle cores, which can be measured experiment
ally by x-ray scattering.
 We also have
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}=N^{1/2}a$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the midblock degree of polymerization and
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the statistical segment length for the midblock.
 The quantity
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is the conentration of 'load bearing strands', which in this case is the
 concentration of triblock copolymer chains with bridging midblocks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\[
\nu=\frac{f\phi_{p}\rho N_{av}}{M}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the molecular weight of the triblock copolymer molecule and
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the polymer density.
 The modulus is strongly concentration dependent because of the concentration
 dependence of the bridging fraction,
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, which is shown in Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:triblock gel briding fractions"

\end_inset

.
